1
00:00:17,017 --> 00:00:19,986
[Rhythmic instrumental music]

2
00:00:20,020 --> 00:00:28,018
* *

3
00:01:37,030 --> 00:01:39,999
[sweeping wistful music]

4
00:01:40,033 --> 00:01:48,031
* *

5
00:01:49,542 --> 00:01:52,511
[sprawling music]

6
00:01:52,545 --> 00:02:00,543
* *

7
00:02:16,769 --> 00:02:17,736
[dog barking]

8
00:02:17,770 --> 00:02:19,670
- Victor.

9
00:02:19,706 --> 00:02:20,968
Victor!

10
00:02:21,007 --> 00:02:21,974
Victor, come on!

11
00:02:22,008 --> 00:02:24,806
Ooph!

12
00:02:24,844 --> 00:02:25,811
Bad dog.

13
00:02:25,845 --> 00:02:27,506
[Barking]

14
00:02:27,547 --> 00:02:29,640
[Birds singing]

15
00:02:29,682 --> 00:02:32,048
[Barking continues]

16
00:02:38,124 --> 00:02:39,751
Oharles!

17
00:02:39,792 --> 00:02:40,724
- Oh, hi.

18
00:02:40,760 --> 00:02:41,852
Oh, what have you been doing?

19
00:02:41,895 --> 00:02:43,760
There's South American stamps
on here.

20
00:02:43,796 --> 00:02:46,594
You must know somebody
in Uruguay, Mr. Razaghi.

21
00:02:46,633 --> 00:02:48,567
- Sort of.

22
00:02:48,601 --> 00:02:50,159
- I hope it's good news.

23
00:02:50,203 --> 00:02:51,192
- Thank you.

24
00:02:54,707 --> 00:02:56,004
[Dog barks]

25
00:02:56,042 --> 00:02:57,771
- "We do not see the need
for an authorized

26
00:02:57,810 --> 00:03:00,506
"biography of Jules Gund
at this time,

27
00:03:00,547 --> 00:03:02,572
nor at any time in the future"?

28
00:03:02,615 --> 00:03:04,310
- Why would they
deny me authorization?

29
00:03:04,350 --> 00:03:05,749
It's not like
everyone in the world

30
00:03:05,785 --> 00:03:09,619
is working on a biography
of Jules Gund.

31
00:03:09,656 --> 00:03:11,123
- Which one is Oaroline Gund?

32
00:03:11,157 --> 00:03:12,419
- The widow.

33
00:03:12,458 --> 00:03:15,450
There's a daughter too,
but she didn't sign.

34
00:03:15,495 --> 00:03:17,520
- So who's Arden Langdon?

35
00:03:17,564 --> 00:03:21,898
- She's the uh...
mistress, I guess.

36
00:03:21,935 --> 00:03:23,630
Adam Gund, that's the brother.

37
00:03:23,670 --> 00:03:25,729
And Ocho Rios is the place

38
00:03:25,772 --> 00:03:28,070
where they all lived together
when Jules Gund was alive.

39
00:03:28,107 --> 00:03:29,506
- That's quite a setup:

40
00:03:29,542 --> 00:03:33,410
The brother, the widow,
the lover, a daughter.

41
00:03:33,446 --> 00:03:36,643
That's probably why they don't
want to authorize a biography.

42
00:03:36,683 --> 00:03:40,244
It's too tortured
and incestuous.

43
00:03:40,286 --> 00:03:42,481
Wait.

44
00:03:42,522 --> 00:03:44,683
"Your request has prompted
much discussion

45
00:03:44,724 --> 00:03:46,988
amongst the trustees."

46
00:03:47,026 --> 00:03:50,291
That could mean
they don't all agree.

47
00:03:52,031 --> 00:03:54,363
[Keys jingling]

48
00:04:04,143 --> 00:04:05,974
You'll have to go to Uruguay.

49
00:04:06,012 --> 00:04:07,377
- What?

50
00:04:07,413 --> 00:04:08,903
After that letter?

51
00:04:08,948 --> 00:04:10,142
- Oonfront the three executors

52
00:04:10,183 --> 00:04:11,946
and make them
change their minds.

53
00:04:11,985 --> 00:04:13,782
It may be easier than you think.

54
00:04:13,820 --> 00:04:15,219
- But they said "no."

55
00:04:15,255 --> 00:04:17,416
- Mm.

56
00:04:17,457 --> 00:04:18,481
You know perfectly well

57
00:04:18,524 --> 00:04:20,116
that without
getting their permission,

58
00:04:20,159 --> 00:04:22,457
there's no fellowship, no money,
no biography,

59
00:04:22,495 --> 00:04:26,295
and no new contract for you
at the university.

60
00:04:26,332 --> 00:04:29,665
Omar, you'll never
get another teaching job.

61
00:04:29,702 --> 00:04:32,728
And what else can you do?

62
00:04:32,772 --> 00:04:33,966
- Nothing.

63
00:04:34,007 --> 00:04:35,167
- Exactly.

64
00:04:52,191 --> 00:04:54,022
I forgot to heat the milk.

65
00:04:54,060 --> 00:04:55,425
Do you think it matters?

66
00:04:55,461 --> 00:04:58,828
- I've never heard of a sublet
that comes with a dog,

67
00:04:58,865 --> 00:05:01,163
and one
with such an elaborate diet.

68
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:02,792
[Cracking]

69
00:05:07,874 --> 00:05:11,275
- [Sighs]

70
00:05:11,311 --> 00:05:13,836
- How could you do that,
fall in a puddle?

71
00:05:13,880 --> 00:05:15,108
- It wasn't a puddle.

72
00:05:15,148 --> 00:05:17,616
It was quicksand.

73
00:05:17,650 --> 00:05:18,776
- For you, it's quicksand.

74
00:05:18,818 --> 00:05:21,286
For everyone else,
it's a puddle.

75
00:05:21,321 --> 00:05:23,118
It's like you have this
subconscious drive

76
00:05:23,156 --> 00:05:28,788
to fall in, to mess up.

77
00:05:28,828 --> 00:05:30,420
I think I should come with you

78
00:05:30,463 --> 00:05:32,454
to Uruguay.

79
00:05:32,498 --> 00:05:34,398
I've had more experience
with things like that.

80
00:05:34,434 --> 00:05:35,458
- No.

81
00:05:35,501 --> 00:05:37,230
I think I should go by myself,

82
00:05:37,270 --> 00:05:41,468
if I decide to go.

83
00:05:41,507 --> 00:05:43,475
- Well, if you decide to go,

84
00:05:43,509 --> 00:05:46,637
I think it would be better
for us to do it together.

85
00:05:46,679 --> 00:05:50,809
Better for us
individually and as a couple.

86
00:05:50,850 --> 00:05:53,080
- I think it'll be better
for both of us

87
00:05:53,119 --> 00:05:54,916
individually and as a couple

88
00:05:54,954 --> 00:05:56,751
if I were to go by myself.

89
00:05:56,789 --> 00:05:58,882
But I appreciate your offer.

90
00:05:58,925 --> 00:06:00,916
- You appreciate my offer?

91
00:06:00,960 --> 00:06:02,951
- Mm-hmm.

92
00:06:02,995 --> 00:06:06,089
- Omar, it's me, Deirdre.

93
00:06:06,132 --> 00:06:08,726
You don't appreciate my offer.

94
00:06:08,768 --> 00:06:11,532
- I almost drowned in quicksand.

95
00:06:11,571 --> 00:06:13,596
I saw my life
flash before my eyes,

96
00:06:13,639 --> 00:06:17,268
and I did not like what I saw.

97
00:06:17,310 --> 00:06:19,278
I've decided to change my life.

98
00:06:19,312 --> 00:06:22,213
I have to be,
you know, more independent.

99
00:06:22,248 --> 00:06:23,476
Like other people.

100
00:06:35,094 --> 00:06:40,794
[Sighs]

101
00:06:40,833 --> 00:06:43,393
- I don't want you
to be like other people,

102
00:06:43,436 --> 00:06:44,994
to change.

103
00:06:50,576 --> 00:06:51,975
[Dog barks]

104
00:06:52,011 --> 00:06:53,979
[Barking continues]

105
00:06:54,013 --> 00:06:55,640
- Oh, what's wrong, buddy?

106
00:06:55,681 --> 00:06:57,649
You want to go outside?
Let's go outside.

107
00:06:57,683 --> 00:06:58,980
Oome on.

108
00:06:59,018 --> 00:06:59,985
Oome on!

109
00:07:00,019 --> 00:07:01,987
Oh.
Buddy.

110
00:07:02,021 --> 00:07:02,988
- Hopeless.

111
00:07:03,022 --> 00:07:05,252
- Out you go.

112
00:07:05,291 --> 00:07:06,280
[Door shuts]

113
00:07:06,325 --> 00:07:09,317
[Distant barking]

114
00:07:18,971 --> 00:07:20,939
- If you fly to Miami first,

115
00:07:20,973 --> 00:07:24,170
it's nonstop from there
to Montevideo.

116
00:07:24,210 --> 00:07:28,806
But that's horribly expensive.

117
00:07:28,848 --> 00:07:30,281
- What about Victor?

118
00:07:30,316 --> 00:07:31,749
- He's not your dog.

119
00:07:31,784 --> 00:07:32,876
We'll put him in a pound.

120
00:07:32,919 --> 00:07:35,717
Most of them
have a 30-day grace period.

121
00:07:35,755 --> 00:07:37,518
You can redeem him
when you get back.

122
00:07:37,557 --> 00:07:39,354
- Deirdre,

123
00:07:39,392 --> 00:07:40,450
he's part of the house-sit.

124
00:07:40,493 --> 00:07:41,619
I'm responsible for him.

125
00:07:41,661 --> 00:07:47,566
We can't just throw him
in the pound.

126
00:07:47,600 --> 00:07:49,124
- Ah, this is better.

127
00:07:49,168 --> 00:07:51,227
From Houston to Sao Paulo,

128
00:07:51,270 --> 00:07:53,465
then Montevideo.

129
00:07:53,506 --> 00:07:55,872
For some reason,
it's much cheaper.

130
00:07:55,908 --> 00:07:59,309
Ah, it takes much longer.

131
00:07:59,345 --> 00:08:00,937
Don't do that now.

132
00:08:03,950 --> 00:08:06,441
[Keyboard clacking]

133
00:08:08,621 --> 00:08:10,521
I'm hurt.

134
00:08:10,556 --> 00:08:12,615
[Sighs deeply]

135
00:08:19,131 --> 00:08:22,430
[Birds singing]

136
00:08:22,468 --> 00:08:23,958
[Horse neighs]

137
00:08:27,874 --> 00:08:31,002
[Indistinct voices and whistles]

138
00:08:54,834 --> 00:08:55,801
<i>- Senor.</i>

139
00:08:55,835 --> 00:08:57,826
<i>- S¨ª.
- Por favor.</i>

140
00:08:59,705 --> 00:09:02,697
[Both speaking Spanish]

141
00:09:37,877 --> 00:09:40,869
[Excited chatter]

142
00:10:03,336 --> 00:10:07,466
[Cattle lowing]

143
00:10:07,506 --> 00:10:08,837
- [Whistling]

144
00:10:12,511 --> 00:10:15,503
[Indistinct shouting]

145
00:10:36,736 --> 00:10:38,363
- Are you coming to Ocho Rios?

146
00:10:38,404 --> 00:10:39,666
That's my house.

147
00:10:39,705 --> 00:10:40,831
- You speak English.

148
00:10:40,873 --> 00:10:41,840
- Of course.

149
00:10:41,874 --> 00:10:43,171
And Spanish.

150
00:10:43,209 --> 00:10:44,608
- I'm Omar.

151
00:10:44,644 --> 00:10:46,236
Omar Razaghi.

152
00:10:46,278 --> 00:10:47,438
- I'm Portia.

153
00:10:47,480 --> 00:10:49,448
Why are you coming to Ocho Rios?

154
00:10:49,482 --> 00:10:50,881
- I want to write a book.

155
00:10:50,916 --> 00:10:54,352
I want to write a biography
about Jules Gund.

156
00:10:54,387 --> 00:10:56,014
Have you heard of him?

157
00:10:56,055 --> 00:10:57,579
- He was my father.

158
00:10:57,623 --> 00:10:59,682
- Your father?

159
00:10:59,725 --> 00:11:01,056
- Mm-hmm.

160
00:11:23,115 --> 00:11:24,082
[Horse snorts]

161
00:11:24,116 --> 00:11:25,845
[Dog barking]

162
00:11:59,885 --> 00:12:00,874
This is Omar.

163
00:12:00,920 --> 00:12:02,285
He's writing a book.

164
00:12:02,321 --> 00:12:03,720
This is my mother.

165
00:12:03,756 --> 00:12:05,485
- Mrs. Gund?

166
00:12:05,524 --> 00:12:07,583
I'm Omar Razaghi.

167
00:12:07,626 --> 00:12:08,923
I wrote you the letter

168
00:12:08,961 --> 00:12:10,292
about the biography.

169
00:12:10,329 --> 00:12:13,127
- My name's Arden Langdon.

170
00:12:13,165 --> 00:12:15,463
Oaroline...

171
00:12:15,501 --> 00:12:18,629
she's Mrs. Gund.

172
00:12:18,671 --> 00:12:19,968
But we wrote to you.

173
00:12:20,005 --> 00:12:21,097
We said no.

174
00:12:21,140 --> 00:12:22,630
We very definitely said no.

175
00:12:22,675 --> 00:12:25,143
- Yes, that's why I'm here.

176
00:12:25,177 --> 00:12:27,737
I'm hoping
you'll change your minds.

177
00:12:27,780 --> 00:12:29,771
I guess
I should have written first.

178
00:12:29,815 --> 00:12:32,375
It was very wrong of me
to come like this.

179
00:12:32,418 --> 00:12:34,181
I have to find a hotel.

180
00:12:34,220 --> 00:12:35,585
- Where?

181
00:12:35,621 --> 00:12:38,488
There's nothing except
this place for miles and miles.

182
00:12:38,524 --> 00:12:40,321
- I can sleep outdoors

183
00:12:40,359 --> 00:12:41,451
in the garden,

184
00:12:41,494 --> 00:12:42,620
if you'll let me.

185
00:12:42,661 --> 00:12:43,821
- Don't be ridiculous.

186
00:12:43,863 --> 00:12:44,921
Now that you're here,

187
00:12:44,964 --> 00:12:46,488
there's nowhere else
for you to go,

188
00:12:46,532 --> 00:12:49,160
so till we can get you
back into town,

189
00:12:49,201 --> 00:12:50,828
we'll have to let you stay.

190
00:12:50,870 --> 00:12:52,462
- Really?

191
00:12:56,375 --> 00:12:57,865
[Horse neighs]

192
00:13:44,757 --> 00:13:46,486
- Mad women and Englishmen:

193
00:13:46,525 --> 00:13:49,323
Why they would want to walk here
in the sun is beyond me.

194
00:13:49,361 --> 00:13:53,889
Of course, those two ladies
are always beyond me.

195
00:13:53,933 --> 00:13:58,597
Oan you help me with my cravat,
please?

196
00:13:58,637 --> 00:14:00,229
You know,
I've always liked this cravat.

197
00:14:00,272 --> 00:14:02,797
I bought it in Venice in 1966.

198
00:14:02,842 --> 00:14:04,275
I must have been happy
at the time.

199
00:14:04,310 --> 00:14:07,711
Otherwise, why would I have
bought such a beautiful thing?

200
00:14:07,746 --> 00:14:12,046
I look very handsome in that.

201
00:14:12,084 --> 00:14:14,575
- They're walking like...

202
00:14:14,620 --> 00:14:16,053
they're bringing important news.

203
00:14:16,088 --> 00:14:18,886
- Oh, what news?

204
00:14:18,924 --> 00:14:21,950
Great tidings at Ocho Rios.

205
00:14:21,994 --> 00:14:24,292
They do look serious,
don't they?

206
00:14:24,330 --> 00:14:26,560
Supposing we...

207
00:14:26,599 --> 00:14:29,466
stuck by our decision
to refuse authorization.

208
00:14:29,501 --> 00:14:31,969
- Then he shall have come
very far for nothing.

209
00:14:32,004 --> 00:14:34,973
- Yes, but he can still
write the biography

210
00:14:35,007 --> 00:14:36,474
without authorization.

211
00:14:36,508 --> 00:14:39,238
That is,
without our help and consent.

212
00:14:39,278 --> 00:14:41,508
That would give him
quite a free hand, wouldn't it?

213
00:14:41,547 --> 00:14:43,310
To make up things,
to make up stories,

214
00:14:43,349 --> 00:14:45,078
twist the facts.

215
00:14:45,117 --> 00:14:46,414
You know, once these people,

216
00:14:46,452 --> 00:14:48,079
these biographers
turn against you,

217
00:14:48,120 --> 00:14:50,179
they can become quite vicious.

218
00:14:50,222 --> 00:14:52,986
- Oh, he didn't look
as if he could ever be that.

219
00:14:53,025 --> 00:14:54,959
- How do you know?

220
00:14:54,994 --> 00:14:56,291
You only saw him
for five minutes

221
00:14:56,328 --> 00:14:58,660
before at once
inviting him to stay.

222
00:14:58,697 --> 00:15:02,690
- He looked so tired
and helpless somehow.

223
00:15:02,735 --> 00:15:03,759
- And young and handsome.

224
00:15:03,802 --> 00:15:05,099
- Oh, really?

225
00:15:05,137 --> 00:15:06,627
- That has nothing
to do with it.

226
00:15:06,672 --> 00:15:09,368
- Anyway, Jules said he didn't
want a biography of himself.

227
00:15:09,408 --> 00:15:12,673
He said it was like having
one's corpse publicly exhumed.

228
00:15:12,711 --> 00:15:15,509
- Oh, when did he say that?

229
00:15:15,547 --> 00:15:17,174
- In a letter to me years ago.

230
00:15:17,216 --> 00:15:19,446
- [Gasps]
My god.

231
00:15:19,485 --> 00:15:21,885
Well, if we were
held accountable

232
00:15:21,921 --> 00:15:24,116
for the things we wrote in
letters millions of years ago,

233
00:15:24,156 --> 00:15:25,919
my dear,
where would any of us be?

234
00:15:25,958 --> 00:15:27,482
But he must have told you
other things.

235
00:15:27,526 --> 00:15:29,551
Um, for instance,
that he would be married

236
00:15:29,595 --> 00:15:32,063
and faithful to you
forever and ever.

237
00:15:32,097 --> 00:15:33,359
- He was.

238
00:15:33,399 --> 00:15:35,367
He stayed married to me.

239
00:15:35,401 --> 00:15:36,629
- Oh.

240
00:15:36,669 --> 00:15:39,137
And Arden didn't count,
or Portia?

241
00:15:39,171 --> 00:15:41,799
- Oaroline didn't say that.

242
00:15:53,719 --> 00:15:56,244
The days pass,
and we live together,

243
00:15:56,288 --> 00:15:57,812
Oaroline and I,

244
00:15:57,856 --> 00:15:59,323
and we manage it.

245
00:15:59,358 --> 00:16:01,826
Quite well, I think.

246
00:16:01,860 --> 00:16:03,589
And now this.

247
00:16:03,629 --> 00:16:04,926
- [Sighs]

248
00:16:04,964 --> 00:16:08,593
Adam's so moody nowadays.

249
00:16:08,634 --> 00:16:10,431
- It's because of you.

250
00:16:10,469 --> 00:16:13,961
He's afraid you'll leave him.

251
00:16:14,006 --> 00:16:16,531
I used to live like that,

252
00:16:16,575 --> 00:16:21,535
always afraid
that Jules would leave me.

253
00:16:21,580 --> 00:16:24,378
He'd get into those black moods,

254
00:16:24,416 --> 00:16:28,284
not speak to me for days on end,

255
00:16:28,320 --> 00:16:29,878
not to anyone,

256
00:16:29,922 --> 00:16:32,288
not to Oaroline.

257
00:16:32,324 --> 00:16:35,293
And I thought
that she'd turn against me

258
00:16:35,327 --> 00:16:37,955
and get him to send me away.

259
00:16:37,997 --> 00:16:39,396
Where would I go?

260
00:16:40,833 --> 00:16:42,357
Where would I go?

261
00:16:42,401 --> 00:16:45,234
- That's all in the past.

262
00:16:47,506 --> 00:16:50,475
- Yes, it's strange.

263
00:16:50,509 --> 00:16:53,637
Everything's easier.

264
00:16:53,679 --> 00:16:55,647
But now
when some stranger arrives...

265
00:16:55,681 --> 00:16:57,615
- Is he young and handsome?

266
00:16:57,649 --> 00:17:00,675
- It depends
what you mean by that.

267
00:17:00,719 --> 00:17:02,812
Oan you find any more teaspoons?

268
00:17:08,193 --> 00:17:11,185
How can we just send him away?

269
00:17:11,230 --> 00:17:13,255
Tell him,
"Good-bye; go home"?

270
00:17:13,298 --> 00:17:14,458
- We're not.

271
00:17:14,500 --> 00:17:16,092
We're even letting him stay
in the house.

272
00:17:16,135 --> 00:17:17,625
We're being very friendly.

273
00:17:17,669 --> 00:17:20,763
- But then he might start to
think we've changed our minds.

274
00:17:20,806 --> 00:17:22,239
- That's his problem.

275
00:17:22,274 --> 00:17:24,265
I can be friendly
without changing my mind.

276
00:17:24,309 --> 00:17:27,210
- Well, he must have come here
with such hope.

277
00:17:27,246 --> 00:17:29,544
- Let's think about this.

278
00:17:29,581 --> 00:17:32,015
A biography would stimulate
interest in Jules' work,

279
00:17:32,051 --> 00:17:34,383
and that is something that we,
as his executors,

280
00:17:34,420 --> 00:17:35,819
should encourage.

281
00:17:35,854 --> 00:17:39,415
Anyway, let's not make
any hasty decisions, shall we?

282
00:17:39,458 --> 00:17:41,722
- My decision's made,
and it's not hasty.

283
00:17:41,760 --> 00:17:45,719
And Arden, for her own reasons,
is on my side.

284
00:17:45,764 --> 00:17:47,288
You are, aren't you?

285
00:17:47,332 --> 00:17:48,629
Yes, you are.

286
00:17:48,667 --> 00:17:51,966
So that's two
against one, Adam.

287
00:17:52,004 --> 00:17:53,562
- Well, I refuse
to be guided by anything

288
00:17:53,605 --> 00:17:56,369
as stupid as democracy.

289
00:17:56,408 --> 00:17:59,309
[Crickets and frogs chirping]

290
00:17:59,344 --> 00:18:02,074
[Clicking and rustling]

291
00:18:02,114 --> 00:18:03,672
- [Whispering]
Portia.

292
00:18:07,953 --> 00:18:10,251
Mustn't disturb him.

293
00:18:10,289 --> 00:18:12,621
- Are we gonna whisper
all night?

294
00:18:12,658 --> 00:18:14,421
Hmm?

295
00:18:14,460 --> 00:18:17,054
- He's come a long way.
He must be tired.

296
00:18:17,096 --> 00:18:20,065
[Dishes clinking]

297
00:18:20,099 --> 00:18:22,397
[Chirping continues]

298
00:18:22,434 --> 00:18:25,369
[Water dripping]

299
00:18:25,404 --> 00:18:26,371
[Squeaking]

300
00:18:26,405 --> 00:18:27,599
[Pipes rumbling and knocking]

301
00:18:27,639 --> 00:18:31,541
[Water sloshing]

302
00:18:31,577 --> 00:18:32,601
[Squeaking]

303
00:18:32,644 --> 00:18:34,339
[Spraying]

304
00:18:48,227 --> 00:18:51,219
[Dramatic opera music]

305
00:18:51,263 --> 00:18:53,697
[Hose spraying]

306
00:18:53,732 --> 00:19:01,605
* *

307
00:19:01,640 --> 00:19:04,609
[telephone ringing]

308
00:19:04,643 --> 00:19:07,612
[Opera music continues]

309
00:19:07,646 --> 00:19:13,414
* *

310
00:19:13,452 --> 00:19:14,419
- Hello?

311
00:19:14,453 --> 00:19:15,750
[Distant opera music]
- Hello?

312
00:19:15,787 --> 00:19:17,982
I would like to speak
to Omar Razaghi, please.

313
00:19:18,023 --> 00:19:19,081
- Dee!

314
00:19:19,124 --> 00:19:20,557
- Omar?
- Hi.

315
00:19:20,592 --> 00:19:21,684
How did you get this number?

316
00:19:21,727 --> 00:19:22,819
- You don't sound like Omar.

317
00:19:22,861 --> 00:19:24,021
Are you eating something?

318
00:19:24,062 --> 00:19:25,586
- Yes, bread and honey.

319
00:19:25,631 --> 00:19:26,598
- What?

320
00:19:26,632 --> 00:19:27,758
- Honey.

321
00:19:27,799 --> 00:19:29,767
- Darling, I miss you too.

322
00:19:29,801 --> 00:19:31,598
But you won't be away long.

323
00:19:31,637 --> 00:19:32,797
What's it like there?

324
00:19:32,838 --> 00:19:34,100
I guess they're all pretty old.

325
00:19:34,139 --> 00:19:35,800
I only hope they're not senile.

326
00:19:35,841 --> 00:19:37,604
- Well, it might take longer
than we thought.

327
00:19:37,643 --> 00:19:39,543
- Oan't you stop eating
for a minute?

328
00:19:39,578 --> 00:19:40,909
- We have a very bad connection.

329
00:19:40,946 --> 00:19:43,938
- I told you to get a cell phone
when you went down there.

330
00:19:43,982 --> 00:19:45,950
It could have come
out of the fellowship money.

331
00:19:45,984 --> 00:19:47,212
[High-pitched beeping]

332
00:19:47,252 --> 00:19:49,948
- Are you there?
Dee?

333
00:19:49,988 --> 00:19:50,977
- Omar?

334
00:19:51,023 --> 00:19:54,789
[Fax machine beeping
and whirring]

335
00:19:54,826 --> 00:19:56,623
- Dee, are you there?
[Beeping continues]

336
00:19:56,662 --> 00:19:57,856
- Hello?

337
00:19:57,896 --> 00:19:59,454
[Beeping]
Click!

338
00:19:59,498 --> 00:20:01,227
[Electronic whirring]

339
00:20:06,271 --> 00:20:07,966
- Thank you for the bread
and the honey.

340
00:20:08,006 --> 00:20:09,906
It was delicious.

341
00:20:09,942 --> 00:20:11,739
- It's from our own bees.

342
00:20:11,777 --> 00:20:13,472
You know anything about bees?

343
00:20:13,512 --> 00:20:15,139
- Bees.

344
00:20:15,180 --> 00:20:16,807
I know they live in an apiary,

345
00:20:16,848 --> 00:20:19,146
<i>a word derived from ap¨ªs,</i>

346
00:20:19,184 --> 00:20:22,642
which is Latin for "bee."

347
00:20:22,688 --> 00:20:24,918
This is not
very interesting information.

348
00:20:24,957 --> 00:20:25,924
- [Laughs]

349
00:20:25,958 --> 00:20:28,654
[Loud opera music]

350
00:20:28,694 --> 00:20:30,992
- I can't believe it.

351
00:20:31,029 --> 00:20:33,088
You read a book and you think
all about the place,

352
00:20:33,131 --> 00:20:34,928
but you don't really think
that it exists,

353
00:20:34,967 --> 00:20:36,434
let alone that you'll be there.

354
00:20:36,468 --> 00:20:38,436
* *

355
00:20:38,470 --> 00:20:39,596
Let me help you with that.

356
00:20:39,638 --> 00:20:41,003
- Oh.
[Giggles]

357
00:20:41,039 --> 00:20:44,702
- [Indistinct speech]

358
00:20:44,743 --> 00:20:47,712
[Opera music continues]

359
00:20:47,746 --> 00:20:55,744
* *

360
00:20:59,424 --> 00:21:00,948
- Ooming here, to Ocho Rios,

361
00:21:00,993 --> 00:21:03,553
was like coming
to my first home,

362
00:21:03,595 --> 00:21:05,620
the first I ever had.

363
00:21:05,664 --> 00:21:06,790
My parents were divorced,

364
00:21:06,832 --> 00:21:09,801
and I went back and forth
between them.

365
00:21:09,835 --> 00:21:11,803
No one really cared.

366
00:21:11,837 --> 00:21:14,203
They both died in plane crashes,

367
00:21:14,239 --> 00:21:15,968
two different planes.

368
00:21:16,008 --> 00:21:17,635
He was on his way to Prague

369
00:21:17,676 --> 00:21:20,042
for one of his
not very successful films,

370
00:21:20,078 --> 00:21:22,478
and Mother
was going to Hong Kong

371
00:21:22,514 --> 00:21:25,244
to get married...
again.

372
00:21:25,284 --> 00:21:26,581
- All the years in America,

373
00:21:26,618 --> 00:21:28,984
my parents wanted to go back
to Tehran,

374
00:21:29,021 --> 00:21:30,249
but it never worked out.

375
00:21:30,289 --> 00:21:31,415
- What did they do?

376
00:21:31,456 --> 00:21:32,650
- They were doctors,

377
00:21:32,691 --> 00:21:34,488
pediatricians.

378
00:21:34,526 --> 00:21:36,756
They died
four years ago.

379
00:21:36,795 --> 00:21:41,357
First my mother, then my father
after a few months.

380
00:21:41,400 --> 00:21:44,836
So we're both orphans.

381
00:21:44,870 --> 00:21:47,168
- I think I was born an orphan.

382
00:21:47,205 --> 00:21:50,834
I was 18 when Jules
first brought me here.

383
00:21:50,876 --> 00:21:52,776
That was ten years ago.

384
00:21:52,811 --> 00:21:54,779
- I was 18 ten years ago.

385
00:21:54,813 --> 00:21:56,440
You and I are the same age,

386
00:21:56,481 --> 00:21:57,505
born at the same time.

387
00:21:57,549 --> 00:21:59,073
We could be brother and sister.

388
00:21:59,117 --> 00:22:00,209
- Twins.

389
00:22:00,252 --> 00:22:03,847
Only twins
can be born at the same time.

390
00:22:03,889 --> 00:22:06,119
- Oh.

391
00:22:06,158 --> 00:22:07,716
I am Omar Razaghi.

392
00:22:07,759 --> 00:22:09,954
- Yes, I know who you are,
my friend.

393
00:22:09,995 --> 00:22:11,121
You're the biographer

394
00:22:11,163 --> 00:22:14,257
who showed up
in spite of our letter.

395
00:22:14,299 --> 00:22:15,732
And what are you giving him?

396
00:22:15,767 --> 00:22:17,325
Oh, what... tea?

397
00:22:17,369 --> 00:22:18,768
Oh, really, Arden,

398
00:22:18,804 --> 00:22:20,795
you'll have to give him
something better than that

399
00:22:20,839 --> 00:22:22,602
to compensate
for his long journey here

400
00:22:22,641 --> 00:22:23,608
and back.

401
00:22:23,642 --> 00:22:25,405
How about some champagne?

402
00:22:25,444 --> 00:22:26,672
- Ohampagne?

403
00:22:26,712 --> 00:22:28,111
At this time of day?

404
00:22:28,146 --> 00:22:31,638
- Well, is there a special
time of the day for champagne?

405
00:22:31,683 --> 00:22:33,742
Well, if so, it is now.

406
00:22:33,785 --> 00:22:35,252
Hmm?

407
00:22:42,627 --> 00:22:44,322
You're flirting with him.

408
00:22:44,363 --> 00:22:45,330
- What?

409
00:22:45,364 --> 00:22:46,661
- When you start opening up

410
00:22:46,698 --> 00:22:49,166
the beautiful secrets
of your past...

411
00:22:49,201 --> 00:22:51,431
"I was born an orphan"...

412
00:22:51,470 --> 00:22:53,563
that's flirting.

413
00:22:53,605 --> 00:22:55,436
- Oaroline,
try not to tease and provoke.

414
00:22:55,474 --> 00:22:57,271
- Oh, come on.

415
00:22:57,309 --> 00:22:59,004
How often do we have a guest,

416
00:22:59,044 --> 00:23:00,739
even an uninvited one?

417
00:23:06,685 --> 00:23:08,619
- I may not
make it back tonight.

418
00:23:08,653 --> 00:23:09,950
- Why not?

419
00:23:09,988 --> 00:23:11,114
- Business,

420
00:23:11,156 --> 00:23:13,283
as you know perfectly well.

421
00:23:13,325 --> 00:23:16,123
- I know your business
perfectly well:

422
00:23:16,161 --> 00:23:20,723
Antique furniture,
and some of it not so antique.

423
00:23:20,766 --> 00:23:22,393
- We need to raise some cash.

424
00:23:22,434 --> 00:23:23,901
- I know.

425
00:23:23,935 --> 00:23:28,133
- Land taxes are due
next month.

426
00:23:28,173 --> 00:23:30,232
You have all this land;

427
00:23:30,275 --> 00:23:32,470
you pay big taxes on it.
- Mm-hmm.

428
00:23:32,511 --> 00:23:34,672
- You don't try
to make it work for you.

429
00:23:39,451 --> 00:23:41,976
Sorry to spoil your mood,

430
00:23:42,020 --> 00:23:44,250
but try and be sensible.

431
00:23:44,289 --> 00:23:45,586
- I'm willing to be sensible,

432
00:23:45,624 --> 00:23:47,285
but can you imagine
the other two

433
00:23:47,325 --> 00:23:48,952
ever agreeing to anything?

434
00:23:48,994 --> 00:23:50,154
I mean, look what's happening

435
00:23:50,195 --> 00:23:52,823
with this
foolish little biography,

436
00:23:52,864 --> 00:23:56,425
which, for all I know,
could be to our advantage.

437
00:23:56,468 --> 00:23:58,493
But Oaroline's only pleasure
left in life

438
00:23:58,537 --> 00:24:00,596
is to say "no" to everything.

439
00:24:00,639 --> 00:24:03,164
And as for poor Arden,
well...

440
00:24:06,478 --> 00:24:11,108
I wish you had more of a life
of your own.

441
00:24:11,149 --> 00:24:12,275
- I do have.

442
00:24:12,317 --> 00:24:14,376
- Yeah.

443
00:24:14,419 --> 00:24:17,115
It saddens me.

444
00:24:17,155 --> 00:24:19,885
I think I was wrong
to bring you here.

445
00:24:19,925 --> 00:24:22,052
Sorry.

446
00:24:22,093 --> 00:24:23,082
Hey.

447
00:24:24,663 --> 00:24:27,655
- [Speaking Spanish]

448
00:24:49,421 --> 00:24:50,445
<i>- Hola!</i>

449
00:24:53,625 --> 00:24:54,819
Ah.

450
00:24:54,860 --> 00:24:56,657
Hello, darling.

451
00:24:56,695 --> 00:24:57,787
Ohampagne.

452
00:24:57,829 --> 00:24:59,091
[Sighs]

453
00:24:59,130 --> 00:25:01,064
Is there a little drop
for me left, do you think?

454
00:25:01,099 --> 00:25:02,123
Ah, the guest.

455
00:25:02,167 --> 00:25:03,134
- Hello, sir.

456
00:25:03,168 --> 00:25:04,499
- Mr. Ragazi
received our letter,

457
00:25:04,536 --> 00:25:06,299
but as you see,
it did not discourage him

458
00:25:06,338 --> 00:25:08,829
from coming to visit,
so now we're all having a party.

459
00:25:08,874 --> 00:25:10,068
- Oh.

460
00:25:10,108 --> 00:25:12,008
Well, then we must show
Mr. Razaghi... Omar, may I?

461
00:25:12,043 --> 00:25:13,340
- Oh, please.
- Omar.

462
00:25:13,378 --> 00:25:15,869
Yes, we must show Omar
what fine hosts we can be

463
00:25:15,914 --> 00:25:17,643
if, by some miracle,
a guest is washed up

464
00:25:17,682 --> 00:25:19,172
on our lonely shore.

465
00:25:19,217 --> 00:25:21,549
Huh?
What do you say?

466
00:25:21,586 --> 00:25:22,712
A picture show.

467
00:25:22,754 --> 00:25:23,778
Yes, why not?

468
00:25:23,822 --> 00:25:25,619
Portia proposes a picture show.

469
00:25:25,657 --> 00:25:26,954
Her one and only picture show.

470
00:25:26,992 --> 00:25:28,619
[Hums a tune]

471
00:25:28,660 --> 00:25:31,561
Go and show uncle Omar
where the projector is.

472
00:25:31,596 --> 00:25:35,225
Ocho Rios pictures presents...

473
00:25:35,267 --> 00:25:37,132
the Gunds.

474
00:25:37,168 --> 00:25:39,568
Ah.

475
00:25:39,604 --> 00:25:42,232
[Sighs]

476
00:25:42,274 --> 00:25:43,901
- This is very unwise,

477
00:25:43,942 --> 00:25:45,967
as if we're suddenly
his collaborators.

478
00:25:46,011 --> 00:25:47,740
- Well, we're not
showing him anything

479
00:25:47,779 --> 00:25:49,508
he doesn't already know, are we?

480
00:25:49,548 --> 00:25:52,073
After all, Jules' book
was not exactly reticent

481
00:25:52,117 --> 00:25:55,245
about our family affairs,
was it?

482
00:25:55,287 --> 00:25:56,914
Ohampagne.

483
00:25:56,955 --> 00:26:01,016
- I'll get you a glass.

484
00:26:01,059 --> 00:26:02,526
- So...

485
00:26:02,561 --> 00:26:05,155
how are you, my dear?

486
00:26:05,196 --> 00:26:06,527
- Peachy.

487
00:26:06,565 --> 00:26:08,533
- Peachy.

488
00:26:17,475 --> 00:26:19,238
Our parents brought
all this film footage

489
00:26:19,277 --> 00:26:20,437
with them from Germany,

490
00:26:20,478 --> 00:26:22,503
and they used to sit
and watch it

491
00:26:22,547 --> 00:26:24,105
the way we're doing now,

492
00:26:24,149 --> 00:26:29,610
drinking champagne.

493
00:26:29,654 --> 00:26:32,521
When they had to leave Germany
and became refugees,

494
00:26:32,557 --> 00:26:33,990
they were allowed
to settle here,

495
00:26:34,025 --> 00:26:35,219
in Uruguay

496
00:26:35,260 --> 00:26:37,125
on condition
that they bought all this land

497
00:26:37,162 --> 00:26:40,723
and developed it for a mine.

498
00:26:40,765 --> 00:26:44,963
My parents
always traveled in style,

499
00:26:45,003 --> 00:26:49,235
even when they were fleeing
Mr. Hitler and his Nazis.

500
00:26:49,274 --> 00:26:52,471
Always traveled first class.

501
00:26:52,510 --> 00:26:54,808
We lived here
the way they had done in Europe.

502
00:26:54,846 --> 00:26:56,404
We lived in the past,

503
00:26:56,448 --> 00:26:58,143
their past.

504
00:26:58,183 --> 00:27:00,151
They didn't want to know
about the present,

505
00:27:00,185 --> 00:27:02,119
any present anywhere.

506
00:27:02,153 --> 00:27:03,745
South America's
very good for that

507
00:27:03,788 --> 00:27:06,154
if you're a rich foreigner.

508
00:27:33,318 --> 00:27:35,115
- That's my grandfather.

509
00:27:35,153 --> 00:27:36,848
- They never
spoke German again...

510
00:27:36,888 --> 00:27:39,857
[dramatic piano music]

511
00:27:39,891 --> 00:27:41,722
* *

512
00:27:41,760 --> 00:27:42,954
Not even to each other.

513
00:27:42,994 --> 00:27:47,829
* *

514
00:27:47,866 --> 00:27:50,562
- There's mysterious Aunt Sarah.

515
00:27:50,602 --> 00:27:55,801
She left for India
to follow her guru.

516
00:27:55,840 --> 00:27:57,034
Ugh.

517
00:27:57,075 --> 00:28:00,203
There she is,
signing away the family fortune.

518
00:28:00,245 --> 00:28:02,213
[Piano music continues]

519
00:28:02,247 --> 00:28:04,909
* *

520
00:28:04,949 --> 00:28:07,713
They went to Venice
for their honeymoon.

521
00:28:07,752 --> 00:28:10,812
And after that,
they went every year

522
00:28:10,855 --> 00:28:14,518
for as long
as it was still possible.

523
00:28:14,559 --> 00:28:17,858
But then the gondola
was the epitome of Europe,

524
00:28:17,896 --> 00:28:19,295
of their Europe.

525
00:28:24,135 --> 00:28:27,434
They persuaded the gondolier
to sell them his gondola.

526
00:28:27,472 --> 00:28:29,269
They called it
the honeymoon gondola

527
00:28:29,307 --> 00:28:33,266
and they had it shipped
all the way from the Adriatic,

528
00:28:33,311 --> 00:28:34,938
right across the Atlantic,

529
00:28:34,979 --> 00:28:36,776
here to Montevideo.

530
00:28:36,815 --> 00:28:39,784
[Piano music continues]

531
00:28:39,818 --> 00:28:47,315
* *

532
00:28:47,358 --> 00:28:51,818
Their maddest
and saddest enterprise maybe.

533
00:28:54,632 --> 00:28:56,293
[Music stops abruptly]

534
00:28:56,334 --> 00:29:00,532
But you've heard all about
our gondola from Jules' book.

535
00:29:00,572 --> 00:29:03,541
It's still here with us,
rotting in the boathouse.

536
00:29:03,575 --> 00:29:06,567
[Projector whirring]

537
00:29:10,115 --> 00:29:11,548
<i>- Buenos d¨ªas.</i>

538
00:29:11,583 --> 00:29:13,414
- I'm Pete.

539
00:29:13,451 --> 00:29:14,850
You must be Omar.

540
00:29:14,886 --> 00:29:15,853
- Yes.

541
00:29:15,887 --> 00:29:17,411
Hello.

542
00:29:17,455 --> 00:29:18,513
- Hi.

543
00:29:18,556 --> 00:29:21,286
- I'm looking
for the mill house.

544
00:29:21,326 --> 00:29:24,523
Miss Langdon said
it was down this way somewhere.

545
00:29:24,562 --> 00:29:26,962
Mr. Gund has invited me
to lunch.

546
00:29:26,998 --> 00:29:29,762
- He has?

547
00:29:29,801 --> 00:29:31,462
He hasn't told me.

548
00:29:31,503 --> 00:29:33,767
I'm the one who does the cooking
around here.

549
00:29:33,805 --> 00:29:37,605
I haven't bought anything.

550
00:29:37,642 --> 00:29:41,942
<i>He'll have to take you
to the par¨ªlla.</i>

551
00:29:41,980 --> 00:29:43,971
There is no other place.

552
00:29:44,015 --> 00:29:45,710
- Do they take Visa?

553
00:29:45,750 --> 00:29:47,911
- Don't worry about that.

554
00:29:47,952 --> 00:29:51,080
Adam always picks up the tab.

555
00:29:51,122 --> 00:29:53,989
He's very generous.

556
00:29:54,025 --> 00:29:56,118
Get in.

557
00:29:56,161 --> 00:30:01,064
It's a mile away.

558
00:30:01,099 --> 00:30:03,397
This is where I found him,

559
00:30:03,434 --> 00:30:05,061
Jules,

560
00:30:05,103 --> 00:30:07,128
by that big palm.

561
00:30:07,172 --> 00:30:10,471
I was the one who found him.

562
00:30:10,508 --> 00:30:15,070
- So near to the house?

563
00:30:15,113 --> 00:30:16,341
- Oome on.

564
00:30:18,483 --> 00:30:21,475
[Motor rumbling]

565
00:30:24,389 --> 00:30:28,155
Blew the top of his head
right off.

566
00:30:28,193 --> 00:30:30,491
I'm glad it was me
who found him

567
00:30:30,528 --> 00:30:34,157
and not one of the others.

568
00:30:34,199 --> 00:30:37,191
The odd thing
is that we all stayed here.

569
00:30:40,872 --> 00:30:41,998
- No, thank you.

570
00:30:42,040 --> 00:30:44,508
- Anyway,

571
00:30:44,542 --> 00:30:46,601
here we all are...

572
00:30:46,644 --> 00:30:48,168
including me.

573
00:30:48,213 --> 00:30:51,376
- Where are you from originally?

574
00:30:51,416 --> 00:30:54,510
- From Tokunoshima.

575
00:30:54,552 --> 00:30:57,180
A small island.

576
00:30:57,222 --> 00:31:00,555
I was poor with no family.

577
00:31:00,592 --> 00:31:03,288
When I was 14,

578
00:31:03,328 --> 00:31:06,661
someone liked me enough
to take me with him to England.

579
00:31:10,335 --> 00:31:12,633
[Loud clunking]

580
00:31:12,670 --> 00:31:15,468
Here.

581
00:31:15,506 --> 00:31:20,068
I find this old furniture
and make it look older.

582
00:31:20,111 --> 00:31:23,808
A lady comes twice a year
from New York and buys it.

583
00:31:23,848 --> 00:31:28,808
She says I have a good eye.

584
00:31:28,853 --> 00:31:31,617
Adam used to work at Ohristie's
in London.

585
00:31:31,656 --> 00:31:32,623
- Hello, Mr. Gund.

586
00:31:32,657 --> 00:31:33,646
- Hello.

587
00:31:33,691 --> 00:31:35,591
- He sent me to a school there

588
00:31:35,627 --> 00:31:37,424
where I learned everything
about furniture.

589
00:31:37,462 --> 00:31:39,760
That was 25 years ago.

590
00:31:39,797 --> 00:31:41,264
- Yes.

591
00:31:41,299 --> 00:31:44,996
We're about to have our
silver anniversary, aren't we?

592
00:31:45,036 --> 00:31:47,027
Ready?
Should we go?

593
00:31:49,374 --> 00:31:50,841
[Sizzling]

594
00:31:50,875 --> 00:31:52,934
I've ordered us
a platter of grilled meat

595
00:31:52,977 --> 00:31:54,205
and some red wine.

596
00:31:54,245 --> 00:31:55,439
- Not too much for me.

597
00:31:55,480 --> 00:31:57,004
I'm a bit of a lightweight,
I'm afraid.

598
00:31:57,048 --> 00:32:00,017
- Really?
How sad.

599
00:32:00,051 --> 00:32:02,542
What about all those
drunken Persian poets of yours?

600
00:32:02,587 --> 00:32:05,454
What about Hafez?

601
00:32:05,490 --> 00:32:06,548
"Bring me a cup of red wine

602
00:32:06,591 --> 00:32:08,684
that is dark red
and smells of musk..."

603
00:32:08,726 --> 00:32:10,421
- "Don't bring me
that expensive stuff..."

604
00:32:10,461 --> 00:32:11,689
- "That tastes like money..."

605
00:32:11,729 --> 00:32:13,060
both: "And smells like lust."

606
00:32:13,097 --> 00:32:16,066
- [Chuckles]

607
00:32:16,100 --> 00:32:18,796
So now, about the biography.

608
00:32:18,836 --> 00:32:21,304
Please understand,
unlike my two sisters-in-law,

609
00:32:21,339 --> 00:32:22,806
or the two ladies,
I should say,

610
00:32:22,840 --> 00:32:23,829
I'm on your side.

611
00:32:23,875 --> 00:32:25,866
- You are?
- Entirely on your side.

612
00:32:25,910 --> 00:32:27,468
See, I've been trying
to explain to them

613
00:32:27,512 --> 00:32:30,140
that to revive an interest
in Jules Gund and his work,

614
00:32:30,181 --> 00:32:32,809
a biography
would be invaluable to us.

615
00:32:32,850 --> 00:32:34,545
- Well, if only
I could convince everyone.

616
00:32:34,585 --> 00:32:36,143
I would be very respectful
of the past,

617
00:32:36,187 --> 00:32:37,176
everyone's feelings.

618
00:32:37,221 --> 00:32:38,188
- My dear boy,

619
00:32:38,222 --> 00:32:39,246
he was my brother.

620
00:32:39,290 --> 00:32:40,882
I knew him better than anyone.

621
00:32:40,925 --> 00:32:42,256
I knew him when we were still

622
00:32:42,293 --> 00:32:44,284
tearing the wings
off butterflies.

623
00:32:44,329 --> 00:32:45,523
I was eight years older,

624
00:32:45,563 --> 00:32:48,498
but it was he who invented
all the little torments

625
00:32:48,533 --> 00:32:50,330
an older brother
inflicts on the younger.

626
00:32:50,368 --> 00:32:52,199
We were both sent to school
in England.

627
00:32:52,236 --> 00:32:53,464
I was utterly miserable,

628
00:32:53,504 --> 00:32:55,665
but he, when in a system,
was in his element.

629
00:32:55,707 --> 00:32:58,267
I suspect it was there at school
that he began to learn

630
00:32:58,309 --> 00:33:01,506
how to exert power
over those who adored him.

631
00:33:01,546 --> 00:33:05,448
It's that simple.

632
00:33:05,483 --> 00:33:09,613
So we must work together,
you and I.

633
00:33:09,654 --> 00:33:11,952
We must co-conspire.

634
00:33:11,990 --> 00:33:12,957
- [Laughs]

635
00:33:12,991 --> 00:33:14,390
I hadn't thought of conspiring.

636
00:33:14,425 --> 00:33:15,653
- Well, of course not.

637
00:33:19,097 --> 00:33:21,565
Ah!

638
00:33:21,599 --> 00:33:23,396
<i>Grac¨ªas.</i>

639
00:33:23,434 --> 00:33:24,401
- Ooh!

640
00:33:24,435 --> 00:33:26,426
[Speaking Spanish]

641
00:33:36,614 --> 00:33:37,740
- This is Mrs. Van Euwen.

642
00:33:37,782 --> 00:33:40,216
The chatelaine
of Las Golondrinas,

643
00:33:40,251 --> 00:33:41,479
our local grand dame.

644
00:33:41,519 --> 00:33:42,679
Very grand.

645
00:33:48,459 --> 00:33:49,824
- Local color, you know?

646
00:33:49,861 --> 00:33:52,159
I told them all they would see
was red meat.

647
00:33:52,196 --> 00:33:53,254
- Yes.

648
00:33:55,666 --> 00:33:56,792
- Worse,

649
00:33:56,834 --> 00:33:59,598
why do you keep your new friend
away from me?

650
00:33:59,637 --> 00:34:01,434
- Oh, yes, he's very beautiful,
isn't he?

651
00:34:01,472 --> 00:34:03,099
Yes, I thought
you'd be interested.

652
00:34:03,141 --> 00:34:05,735
This is...
he's blushing.

653
00:34:05,777 --> 00:34:07,210
- Ooh!
- This is Omar Razaghi.

654
00:34:07,245 --> 00:34:09,270
He's come to do research
on my brother's biography.

655
00:34:09,313 --> 00:34:10,280
- Mucho gusto.

656
00:34:10,314 --> 00:34:11,406
- Ah!

657
00:34:11,449 --> 00:34:13,110
Then you must research me.

658
00:34:13,151 --> 00:34:15,176
I can tell you
things about Jules

659
00:34:15,219 --> 00:34:16,948
that a brother
could never know...

660
00:34:16,988 --> 00:34:18,853
or a wife or even a mistress.

661
00:34:18,890 --> 00:34:20,118
[Laughs]

662
00:34:20,158 --> 00:34:23,457
You should write his life,
his and Pete's.

663
00:34:23,494 --> 00:34:26,395
That a more interesting story,
yeah.

664
00:34:26,431 --> 00:34:27,455
- Go away.
Go away.

665
00:34:27,498 --> 00:34:29,125
Thank you.
- I go. I go.

666
00:34:29,167 --> 00:34:32,000
You should come
to Las Golondrinas.

667
00:34:48,453 --> 00:34:49,613
- Have a sausage.

668
00:34:49,654 --> 00:34:51,144
- Is it pork?

669
00:34:51,189 --> 00:34:52,156
- Maybe.

670
00:34:52,190 --> 00:34:53,316
I don't know.

671
00:34:53,357 --> 00:34:54,984
[Chuckles]

672
00:34:55,026 --> 00:34:59,156
You don't drink;
you hardly eat meat.

673
00:34:59,197 --> 00:35:01,597
Um... well, as I said before,

674
00:35:01,632 --> 00:35:02,724
I know I can trust you.

675
00:35:02,767 --> 00:35:03,995
I feel I can ask you
for your help

676
00:35:04,035 --> 00:35:06,367
as you're asking for mine.

677
00:35:06,404 --> 00:35:09,032
- Like I said, I'll do anything.

678
00:35:09,073 --> 00:35:11,041
- Wait, wait,
this is non-literary.

679
00:35:11,075 --> 00:35:13,703
It's nothing to do
with the biography.

680
00:35:13,744 --> 00:35:16,042
When our mother... that is,
Jules' mother, my mother...

681
00:35:16,080 --> 00:35:18,048
when our mother arrived here
as a refugee,

682
00:35:18,082 --> 00:35:21,279
she brought with her from
Germany some valuable things,

683
00:35:21,319 --> 00:35:22,877
her jewelry.

684
00:35:22,920 --> 00:35:25,047
Now, I have her jewelry.

685
00:35:25,089 --> 00:35:27,114
And I would like
to dispose of it,

686
00:35:27,158 --> 00:35:32,460
and I would like you to help me
dispose of it.

687
00:35:32,497 --> 00:35:33,759
- Is it legal?

688
00:35:33,798 --> 00:35:34,924
- Is what legal?

689
00:35:34,966 --> 00:35:37,560
- Taking these things
out of the country?

690
00:35:37,602 --> 00:35:39,467
- No, it's moral.

691
00:35:39,504 --> 00:35:40,801
They're my things.

692
00:35:40,838 --> 00:35:42,635
They were my mother's.

693
00:35:42,673 --> 00:35:45,301
When she arrived here,
she hid them away.

694
00:35:45,343 --> 00:35:46,901
Because of her experiences
in Germany,

695
00:35:46,944 --> 00:35:47,911
she trusted no one.

696
00:35:47,945 --> 00:35:49,879
She didn't feel safe anywhere.

697
00:35:49,914 --> 00:35:52,474
Outside of this cocoon
that they built here,

698
00:35:52,517 --> 00:35:56,146
why, she and my father
didn't feel safe on this planet.

699
00:35:56,187 --> 00:35:57,654
[Chuckles]

700
00:35:57,688 --> 00:36:00,748
So after her death,
very shortly after my father's,

701
00:36:00,791 --> 00:36:02,088
I found the jewels.

702
00:36:02,126 --> 00:36:05,095
- Do Arden and Oaroline know
about them?

703
00:36:05,129 --> 00:36:06,096
- Nope.

704
00:36:06,130 --> 00:36:08,098
They know nothing
of that history.

705
00:36:08,132 --> 00:36:09,599
Even Oaroline
hardly knew my mother.

706
00:36:09,634 --> 00:36:14,094
She certainly knew nothing
of what was precious to her.

707
00:36:14,138 --> 00:36:15,935
So I took the jewels.

708
00:36:15,973 --> 00:36:18,999
I felt I could assume
that they were mine

709
00:36:19,043 --> 00:36:22,979
as Oaroline, in due course,
felt free to take what was hers.

710
00:36:23,014 --> 00:36:24,538
- From what your mother left?

711
00:36:24,582 --> 00:36:28,450
- With Oaroline,
it was what my brother left.

712
00:36:28,486 --> 00:36:29,714
Have you never thought,

713
00:36:29,754 --> 00:36:32,552
never suspected that
there might be another book?

714
00:36:32,590 --> 00:36:33,784
<i>- Other than The Gondola?</i>

715
00:36:33,824 --> 00:36:35,416
- Mm-hmm.

716
00:36:35,459 --> 00:36:39,555
- It is well known, Jules Gund
wrote only that one book.

717
00:36:39,597 --> 00:36:43,795
- Well, he was working
on another one when he died.

718
00:36:43,834 --> 00:36:47,065
It is my theory that he died,
or killed himself,

719
00:36:47,104 --> 00:36:50,301
because he couldn't...

720
00:36:50,341 --> 00:36:52,138
couldn't write anymore.

721
00:36:52,176 --> 00:36:53,734
Or because of what
he was writing

722
00:36:53,778 --> 00:36:56,747
or trying to write.

723
00:36:56,781 --> 00:36:58,442
A psychological impasse.

724
00:36:58,482 --> 00:37:00,609
- Oaroline has the manuscript?

725
00:37:00,651 --> 00:37:03,245
- I don't know.
You have to ask her.

726
00:37:03,287 --> 00:37:04,652
But that is not the subject

727
00:37:04,689 --> 00:37:06,850
of our present little talk,
is it?

728
00:37:06,891 --> 00:37:08,085
My jewels.

729
00:37:08,125 --> 00:37:10,525
My need for money.

730
00:37:10,561 --> 00:37:11,789
Ah, here's Pete.

731
00:37:23,140 --> 00:37:24,437
Hail to thee!

732
00:37:55,206 --> 00:37:57,674
[Motor rumbling]

733
00:38:04,115 --> 00:38:05,241
Oome upstairs.
Follow me.

734
00:38:05,283 --> 00:38:06,443
I want to show you something.

735
00:38:11,956 --> 00:38:13,924
It is not for myself
that I need the money;

736
00:38:13,958 --> 00:38:15,016
it is for Pete,

737
00:38:15,059 --> 00:38:18,688
who may be free to leave me.

738
00:38:18,729 --> 00:38:20,287
- Does he want to leave you?

739
00:38:20,331 --> 00:38:21,559
- He should.

740
00:38:21,599 --> 00:38:25,365
He still has a chance at
a better life than with me here.

741
00:38:25,403 --> 00:38:27,530
You know, in order to bring him
here to Uruguay,

742
00:38:27,571 --> 00:38:30,199
I had to adopt him.

743
00:38:30,241 --> 00:38:32,471
Legally, he is my son.

744
00:38:38,382 --> 00:38:42,614
Oome and sit down, please.

745
00:38:42,653 --> 00:38:45,713
- I'll do what you ask.

746
00:38:45,756 --> 00:38:47,951
- Even though it's illegal
and dangerous?

747
00:38:47,992 --> 00:38:50,893
- I think
it's the right thing to do.

748
00:38:50,928 --> 00:38:53,726
If you can trust me
not to screw it up.

749
00:38:53,764 --> 00:38:55,629
- Ah, we shall see.

750
00:38:55,666 --> 00:38:58,430
Please, sit down.

751
00:38:58,469 --> 00:38:59,629
So here's the treasure.

752
00:38:59,670 --> 00:39:01,729
Some of it is mixed up
with my father's.

753
00:39:01,772 --> 00:39:03,672
That's my father's watch.

754
00:39:03,708 --> 00:39:06,108
Mother used to keep them
locked in the safe,

755
00:39:06,143 --> 00:39:09,670
but sometimes she'd take it out
and wear it for me to show me.

756
00:39:09,714 --> 00:39:10,874
And, uh...

757
00:39:10,915 --> 00:39:14,248
I was her favorite, you know,
her firstborn,

758
00:39:14,285 --> 00:39:16,344
her Adam, she called me.

759
00:39:16,387 --> 00:39:17,445
[Chuckles]

760
00:39:17,488 --> 00:39:20,184
Of course,
Jules could never get over that.

761
00:39:20,224 --> 00:39:22,124
She would show me
how she wore them

762
00:39:22,159 --> 00:39:25,356
and where.

763
00:39:25,396 --> 00:39:27,762
This at the opera.

764
00:39:27,798 --> 00:39:29,595
She had much smaller wrists
than mine.

765
00:39:29,633 --> 00:39:31,760
- Wow.
- It's beautiful.

766
00:39:31,802 --> 00:39:32,996
Go on, you can take it.

767
00:39:33,037 --> 00:39:37,098
It's all right.

768
00:39:37,141 --> 00:39:42,977
And these at the Burgtheater.

769
00:39:43,013 --> 00:39:47,109
- [Chuckles]
- Isn't that beautiful?

770
00:39:47,151 --> 00:39:50,848
Oh, yes, and this little horse
was for the races.

771
00:39:50,888 --> 00:39:54,619
And she'd wear this
attached to her cloche hat.

772
00:39:54,658 --> 00:39:57,650
[Bees buzzing]

773
00:40:25,823 --> 00:40:28,815
[Knock at door]

774
00:40:28,859 --> 00:40:31,419
- It's me, Omar Razaghi.

775
00:40:31,462 --> 00:40:33,987
[Door squeaks open]

776
00:40:34,031 --> 00:40:37,933
I hope I'm not disturbing you.

777
00:40:37,968 --> 00:40:39,492
- I'm just having my breakfast.

778
00:40:39,537 --> 00:40:42,700
Oome in.
[Loud cracking]

779
00:40:47,711 --> 00:40:49,440
- Oh.
No, thank you.

780
00:40:58,389 --> 00:41:00,186
- You don't have to say
anything nice about it.

781
00:41:00,224 --> 00:41:01,748
- No, I like it.
It's very interesting.

782
00:41:01,792 --> 00:41:03,384
- It's only a copy.

783
00:41:03,427 --> 00:41:05,588
That's all I do nowadays,
is copies,

784
00:41:05,629 --> 00:41:07,062
copy the masters.

785
00:41:07,097 --> 00:41:08,325
It's safer.

786
00:41:08,365 --> 00:41:11,562
That way,
I don't reveal anything.

787
00:41:11,602 --> 00:41:13,627
It's what art does,

788
00:41:13,671 --> 00:41:14,899
even biography.

789
00:41:14,939 --> 00:41:16,873
Especially biography.

790
00:41:16,907 --> 00:41:19,808
- I would be very discreet.

791
00:41:19,844 --> 00:41:22,404
I would absolutely
respect your wishes

792
00:41:22,446 --> 00:41:23,845
as to what to reveal.

793
00:41:31,055 --> 00:41:33,580
- What if I were to tell you
that Jules explicitly said

794
00:41:33,624 --> 00:41:37,287
he didn't want a biography
of himself?

795
00:41:37,328 --> 00:41:39,592
He wrote it to me in a letter.

796
00:41:39,630 --> 00:41:41,723
I suppose
you'd want to see that letter.

797
00:41:41,765 --> 00:41:42,891
- Well, yes.

798
00:41:42,933 --> 00:41:44,525
I'd like to very much.

799
00:41:44,568 --> 00:41:46,502
- And why
would I show it to you?

800
00:41:46,537 --> 00:41:49,005
I don't know anything about you,

801
00:41:49,039 --> 00:41:54,443
no more than you know about me
or ever will.

802
00:41:54,478 --> 00:41:58,574
What if I were to ask you,
have you ever been in love,

803
00:41:58,616 --> 00:42:02,450
passionately in love?

804
00:42:04,822 --> 00:42:06,619
See, you can't answer me.

805
00:42:06,657 --> 00:42:07,885
You're not sure.

806
00:42:07,925 --> 00:42:09,290
- I am sure.

807
00:42:09,326 --> 00:42:13,387
- Do you have a girlfriend?

808
00:42:13,430 --> 00:42:14,727
A partner?

809
00:42:14,765 --> 00:42:17,063
- Why do you want to know?

810
00:42:17,101 --> 00:42:19,569
- Are you romantically involved?

811
00:42:19,603 --> 00:42:21,537
- Yes.

812
00:42:21,572 --> 00:42:23,130
I suppose I am.

813
00:42:23,173 --> 00:42:24,470
- Suppose?

814
00:42:24,508 --> 00:42:26,976
That doesn't sound very
positive, let alone passionate.

815
00:42:27,011 --> 00:42:29,809
- We've been together two years.

816
00:42:29,847 --> 00:42:32,577
Her name is Deirdre.

817
00:42:32,616 --> 00:42:34,481
If it weren't for her,
I wouldn't be here.

818
00:42:34,518 --> 00:42:38,420
I mean, here in Uruguay.

819
00:42:38,455 --> 00:42:40,980
I would have accepted
your decision.

820
00:42:41,025 --> 00:42:42,185
I would have given up.

821
00:42:42,226 --> 00:42:45,320
- I see.

822
00:42:45,362 --> 00:42:48,331
Sit.

823
00:42:48,365 --> 00:42:51,892
So it is your friend Deirdre

824
00:42:51,936 --> 00:42:54,131
who made you come
to change our minds.

825
00:42:54,171 --> 00:42:55,763
And what if
you can't change our minds?

826
00:42:55,806 --> 00:42:57,000
What will she think?

827
00:42:57,041 --> 00:42:59,305
She'll think you failed.

828
00:42:59,343 --> 00:43:00,332
- Yes.

829
00:43:00,377 --> 00:43:02,106
And she'd be right.

830
00:43:02,146 --> 00:43:03,636
I will have failed.

831
00:43:03,681 --> 00:43:05,546
- Sometimes it's good to fail,

832
00:43:05,583 --> 00:43:07,107
to try but to fail.

833
00:43:07,151 --> 00:43:08,812
There's nothing ignoble in that.

834
00:43:08,852 --> 00:43:09,944
- You don't understand.

835
00:43:09,987 --> 00:43:11,386
Everything depends on it:

836
00:43:11,422 --> 00:43:13,287
My job, my career,

837
00:43:13,324 --> 00:43:15,815
maybe my relationship
with my girlfriend.

838
00:43:18,829 --> 00:43:22,390
- You're so young.

839
00:43:22,433 --> 00:43:24,560
Are you sure that's
what you want your life to be

840
00:43:24,602 --> 00:43:27,469
forever and ever:

841
00:43:27,504 --> 00:43:30,496
That job, that career,

842
00:43:30,541 --> 00:43:32,839
that girlfriend?

843
00:43:36,447 --> 00:43:41,646
I'll show you
a real picture I painted.

844
00:43:41,685 --> 00:43:44,153
It's Jules, only it's not him,

845
00:43:44,188 --> 00:43:46,884
not as he really was,
which only I knew.

846
00:43:46,924 --> 00:43:49,893
You don't see it
because I couldn't paint it.

847
00:43:49,927 --> 00:43:54,921
I wasn't good enough
to paint it.

848
00:43:54,965 --> 00:43:57,866
I suppose now you'll write
how the widow of Jules Gund

849
00:43:57,901 --> 00:43:59,892
is sitting
in a south American jungle

850
00:43:59,937 --> 00:44:03,566
painting atrocious paintings
and slowly going mad

851
00:44:03,607 --> 00:44:05,040
or not so slowly.

852
00:44:05,075 --> 00:44:08,067
- I promise to write nothing
you don't want me to write.

853
00:44:08,112 --> 00:44:10,103
- Point is,
I want you to write nothing.

854
00:44:10,147 --> 00:44:11,842
- If you could just give me
one reason.

855
00:44:11,882 --> 00:44:13,110
- I don't have a reason.

856
00:44:13,150 --> 00:44:15,311
As anyone will tell you,
I am an unreasonable person.

857
00:44:15,352 --> 00:44:16,876
Jules himself
would have told you that

858
00:44:16,920 --> 00:44:17,944
if he'd still been here.

859
00:44:17,988 --> 00:44:20,115
In fact,
it's the very word he used

860
00:44:20,157 --> 00:44:22,785
when he felt I wasn't
being accommodating enough

861
00:44:22,826 --> 00:44:24,453
to his arrangements.

862
00:44:24,495 --> 00:44:26,588
"You're so unreasonable,
Oaroline."

863
00:44:26,630 --> 00:44:27,597
- I'm sorry.

864
00:44:27,631 --> 00:44:29,030
I shouldn't have come here.

865
00:44:29,066 --> 00:44:30,966
- Don't apologize.

866
00:44:31,001 --> 00:44:33,401
No, it's good sometimes
to hear another voice.

867
00:44:33,437 --> 00:44:34,426
I was beginning to think

868
00:44:34,471 --> 00:44:35,995
that apart from
our little group here,

869
00:44:36,040 --> 00:44:37,837
there was no one else
left in the world.

870
00:44:39,343 --> 00:44:42,312
[Plaintive woodwind music]

871
00:44:42,346 --> 00:44:50,344
* *

872
00:44:52,356 --> 00:44:55,348
[crickets and frogs chirping]

873
00:45:12,009 --> 00:45:13,874
- Do you want to hear
how Arden met Jules?

874
00:45:13,911 --> 00:45:15,071
- Yes.

875
00:45:15,112 --> 00:45:17,376
- Omar doesn't want
to know that at all.

876
00:45:17,414 --> 00:45:21,111
- He's writing a book;
he has to know everything.

877
00:45:21,151 --> 00:45:24,450
- Mm-hmm.

878
00:45:24,488 --> 00:45:28,891
- Um... I was traveling
around Spain

879
00:45:28,926 --> 00:45:32,384
when I met some people
going to Uruguay.

880
00:45:32,429 --> 00:45:34,454
So I went with them,

881
00:45:34,498 --> 00:45:37,296
and they turned out
to be a missionary group

882
00:45:37,334 --> 00:45:41,395
sent to convert
the heathen of south America.

883
00:45:41,438 --> 00:45:43,065
[Both laugh]

884
00:45:43,107 --> 00:45:44,938
- Don't laugh.

885
00:45:44,975 --> 00:45:48,570
Our name was joyful noise.

886
00:45:48,612 --> 00:45:50,477
[Both laugh]

887
00:45:50,514 --> 00:45:54,644
And we went around in a bus
and gave concerts in the street.

888
00:45:54,685 --> 00:45:56,152
We never drew much of a crowd,

889
00:45:56,186 --> 00:45:59,815
but people listened
very politely.

890
00:45:59,857 --> 00:46:01,256
But by the time we'd finished,

891
00:46:01,291 --> 00:46:03,919
there was usually
only one or two left.

892
00:46:03,961 --> 00:46:07,021
But we went right on singing
and playing.

893
00:46:07,064 --> 00:46:11,592
- Arden shook the tambourine.

894
00:46:11,635 --> 00:46:16,595
- Anyway, one day,
Jules stopped to listen.

895
00:46:16,640 --> 00:46:21,202
And when we were through,
he came up to me and said,

896
00:46:21,245 --> 00:46:22,769
"What are you doing?

897
00:46:22,813 --> 00:46:25,281
And why are you doing it?"

898
00:46:25,315 --> 00:46:27,044
So I stopped.

899
00:46:27,084 --> 00:46:28,483
- And then I was born.

900
00:46:28,519 --> 00:46:30,885
- Well,
not quite so quickly, darling.

901
00:46:30,921 --> 00:46:32,980
- Nine months later, anyway.

902
00:47:17,901 --> 00:47:20,927
- I'm packing a picnic lunch.

903
00:47:20,971 --> 00:47:24,099
- Why are you going on a picnic?

904
00:47:24,141 --> 00:47:26,701
- I'm taking Omar
to show him the gondola.

905
00:47:26,743 --> 00:47:30,110
- Why?

906
00:47:30,147 --> 00:47:32,047
As if that gondola
isn't the most ludicrous

907
00:47:32,082 --> 00:47:34,607
of all the ludicrous
collected items here.

908
00:47:34,651 --> 00:47:35,777
- I don't feel that.

909
00:47:35,819 --> 00:47:39,277
- No...

910
00:47:39,323 --> 00:47:43,783
You've changed your mind
about the biography.

911
00:47:43,827 --> 00:47:46,295
Well, haven't you?

912
00:47:46,330 --> 00:47:47,797
- [Sighs]

913
00:47:47,831 --> 00:47:50,299
Why shouldn't he
write the biography?

914
00:47:50,334 --> 00:47:51,631
He seems...

915
00:47:51,668 --> 00:47:54,967
he's just the right person
to understand Jules.

916
00:47:55,005 --> 00:47:56,632
- In what way
is he the right person?

917
00:47:56,673 --> 00:47:58,800
Because he's good-looking
and charming

918
00:47:58,842 --> 00:48:01,902
and because he's charmed you?

919
00:48:01,945 --> 00:48:05,574
What is it?

920
00:48:05,616 --> 00:48:07,106
I'm sorry.

921
00:48:07,150 --> 00:48:11,086
It's just that what we decided
before still stands for me.

922
00:48:11,121 --> 00:48:12,748
Maybe I shouldn't tell you this.

923
00:48:12,789 --> 00:48:15,815
- Tell me what?

924
00:48:15,859 --> 00:48:17,690
- Do you know
he's in love with someone?

925
00:48:20,898 --> 00:48:23,332
- I didn't know that.

926
00:48:23,367 --> 00:48:24,994
- He told me he has a fianc¨¦e.

927
00:48:25,035 --> 00:48:26,093
Maybe they're not engaged,

928
00:48:26,136 --> 00:48:28,297
but he has
a romantic attachment.

929
00:48:28,338 --> 00:48:30,932
- Why are you telling me this?

930
00:48:30,974 --> 00:48:33,306
- Because I thought
you should know.

931
00:48:33,343 --> 00:48:35,538
- It has nothing to do
with anything.

932
00:48:35,579 --> 00:48:40,278
- I never said that it had,
but I wouldn't blame you.

933
00:48:40,317 --> 00:48:41,477
You're lonely.

934
00:48:41,518 --> 00:48:44,112
- I'm not lonely.

935
00:48:44,154 --> 00:48:46,281
Or maybe I am
and I didn't know it

936
00:48:46,323 --> 00:48:48,848
until there was a new person.

937
00:48:48,892 --> 00:48:54,057
When do we ever see anyone
or get to talk to anyone?

938
00:48:54,097 --> 00:48:55,792
And now...

939
00:48:55,832 --> 00:48:58,130
why are you talking to me
like this?

940
00:48:58,168 --> 00:48:59,829
Why do you want to hurt me?

941
00:48:59,870 --> 00:49:02,998
- I don't want to hurt you.

942
00:49:03,040 --> 00:49:05,668
I never wanted to hurt you.

943
00:49:05,709 --> 00:49:08,405
- Hola!

944
00:49:08,445 --> 00:49:10,709
- So you're off
to see the gondola.

945
00:49:10,747 --> 00:49:12,078
- Oh, yes.

946
00:49:12,115 --> 00:49:15,744
You'll be coming with us?

947
00:49:15,786 --> 00:49:18,550
- I've been there.

948
00:49:20,691 --> 00:49:21,919
- [Sighs]
Mmm.

949
00:49:21,959 --> 00:49:24,154
- Maybe we shouldn't go.

950
00:49:24,194 --> 00:49:25,422
It's a long way.

951
00:49:25,462 --> 00:49:28,898
- Uh, well, if you're not
feeling up to it.

952
00:49:28,932 --> 00:49:31,765
- Well, if you're not allowed
to write the biography,

953
00:49:31,802 --> 00:49:33,531
there's no point in going.

954
00:49:33,570 --> 00:49:36,038
And Oaroline
won't change her mind.

955
00:49:36,073 --> 00:49:38,268
That's the way she is.

956
00:49:38,308 --> 00:49:41,072
She has a much stronger
character than I have.

957
00:49:41,111 --> 00:49:42,100
- That's not true.

958
00:49:42,145 --> 00:49:43,442
- Oh, but it is.

959
00:49:43,480 --> 00:49:44,708
Jules used to say that

960
00:49:44,748 --> 00:49:48,206
any breeze could come
and blow me any which way.

961
00:49:48,251 --> 00:49:51,015
But actually,
why shouldn't we go?

962
00:49:51,054 --> 00:49:52,112
- Right.

963
00:49:52,155 --> 00:49:53,622
Why shouldn't we?

964
00:49:53,657 --> 00:49:56,626
[Hooves clopping]

965
00:49:56,660 --> 00:49:59,686
[Cattle lowing]

966
00:50:02,499 --> 00:50:04,467
[Horse whinnies]

967
00:50:04,501 --> 00:50:06,526
- Whoa.

968
00:50:06,570 --> 00:50:10,097
[Clanking]

969
00:50:10,140 --> 00:50:12,301
[Motor rumbling]

970
00:50:12,342 --> 00:50:16,642
[Brakes screeching]

971
00:50:16,680 --> 00:50:19,171
[Brakes hiss]

972
00:50:19,216 --> 00:50:20,205
[Doors squeak]

973
00:50:22,819 --> 00:50:24,252
Who won?

974
00:50:24,287 --> 00:50:25,811
- We did.

975
00:50:27,157 --> 00:50:29,182
- [Speaks Spanish]

976
00:50:30,427 --> 00:50:31,951
[Motor rumbles]

977
00:50:31,995 --> 00:50:33,587
- I have to go find Arden.

978
00:50:33,630 --> 00:50:35,495
- She is showing Omar
the gondola.

979
00:50:35,532 --> 00:50:36,590
- Without me?

980
00:50:36,633 --> 00:50:38,328
- They'll take you another time.

981
00:50:38,368 --> 00:50:40,268
- What if Omar goes away?

982
00:50:40,303 --> 00:50:41,668
Is he going away?

983
00:50:41,705 --> 00:50:45,163
- Do you want him to stay?

984
00:50:45,208 --> 00:50:46,937
- Definitely.

985
00:50:51,982 --> 00:50:53,847
- Do you live alone?

986
00:50:53,884 --> 00:50:55,511
- Yes.

987
00:50:55,552 --> 00:50:58,453
- But you have a girlfriend.

988
00:50:58,488 --> 00:51:02,117
- Yes.
I do.

989
00:51:02,159 --> 00:51:04,218
- What's her name?

990
00:51:04,261 --> 00:51:05,523
- Her name is Deirdre.

991
00:51:05,562 --> 00:51:09,999
She teaches
at the same university.

992
00:51:10,033 --> 00:51:11,625
- What does she teach?

993
00:51:11,668 --> 00:51:14,466
- Literature, like me.

994
00:51:14,504 --> 00:51:17,962
She's a good teacher.

995
00:51:18,008 --> 00:51:20,670
Much better than I'll ever be.

996
00:51:20,710 --> 00:51:24,146
The great Russians
and German poets.

997
00:51:24,181 --> 00:51:25,307
[Chuckles]

998
00:51:25,348 --> 00:51:27,748
- Sorry, I'm being rude.

999
00:51:27,784 --> 00:51:29,649
I'm not used to meeting
new people,

1000
00:51:29,686 --> 00:51:34,089
so I don't know
how to behave anymore.

1001
00:51:34,124 --> 00:51:36,115
I shouldn't ask you
all those questions.

1002
00:51:36,159 --> 00:51:39,128
- But think of all the questions
I want to ask you.

1003
00:51:42,466 --> 00:51:45,162
Is all of this your land?

1004
00:51:45,202 --> 00:51:48,933
- Pete keeps trying
to make us sell some of it,

1005
00:51:48,972 --> 00:51:53,102
or at least lease it
for a vineyard or something.

1006
00:51:53,143 --> 00:51:54,667
And we could do with the money,

1007
00:51:54,711 --> 00:51:57,373
but you see how we all are.

1008
00:52:05,088 --> 00:52:08,251
- There's no quicksand here,
is there?

1009
00:52:08,291 --> 00:52:10,350
A swamp you could sink into?

1010
00:52:10,393 --> 00:52:13,453
- Oh, well, yes,
there's lots of swamps.

1011
00:52:13,497 --> 00:52:14,828
So watch out.

1012
00:52:21,037 --> 00:52:23,938
What's wrong?

1013
00:52:23,974 --> 00:52:26,966
- I...

1014
00:52:27,010 --> 00:52:29,808
I feel a bit strange.

1015
00:52:29,846 --> 00:52:31,404
Oan't be the altitude.

1016
00:52:31,448 --> 00:52:33,746
- Oh, no, we're at sea level.

1017
00:52:33,783 --> 00:52:35,910
Maybe you're just hungry.

1018
00:52:35,952 --> 00:52:36,919
Oome on.

1019
00:52:36,953 --> 00:52:39,717
- Maybe.

1020
00:52:39,756 --> 00:52:41,587
- I want you to know,

1021
00:52:41,625 --> 00:52:44,992
I've changed my mind
about the biography.

1022
00:52:45,028 --> 00:52:49,590
Why should I be afraid
of stirring up bad memories?

1023
00:52:49,633 --> 00:52:50,691
There aren't any.

1024
00:52:50,734 --> 00:52:52,668
There's Portia

1025
00:52:52,702 --> 00:52:56,604
and this lovely place
for her to grow up in.

1026
00:52:56,640 --> 00:52:58,938
I want you to write the book.

1027
00:52:58,975 --> 00:53:01,375
Like Adam, I'm on your side.

1028
00:53:01,411 --> 00:53:03,379
I give you my... what is it?

1029
00:53:03,413 --> 00:53:05,643
My... my authorization.

1030
00:53:09,986 --> 00:53:12,181
- [Chuckles]

1031
00:53:12,222 --> 00:53:16,215
You know, I came here
to write one kind of book.

1032
00:53:16,259 --> 00:53:17,658
- No, thanks.

1033
00:53:21,331 --> 00:53:25,961
- And now it's turning
into something different.

1034
00:53:26,002 --> 00:53:30,803
Like, it's no longer
about Jules

1035
00:53:30,840 --> 00:53:33,968
but about you... all of you.

1036
00:53:34,010 --> 00:53:36,638
And your life here

1037
00:53:36,680 --> 00:53:39,808
and even about me here with you.

1038
00:53:39,849 --> 00:53:42,147
Does that make sense?

1039
00:53:42,185 --> 00:53:44,551
No? It doesn't?

1040
00:53:44,588 --> 00:53:48,251
- Well, not entirely,
but you said you were feeling...

1041
00:53:48,291 --> 00:53:50,486
[loud clanking]

1042
00:53:50,527 --> 00:53:51,516
[Clattering]

1043
00:53:51,561 --> 00:53:53,825
[Hinges squeaking]

1044
00:53:53,863 --> 00:53:55,023
- Oh.

1045
00:54:00,971 --> 00:54:02,962
[Chuckling]

1046
00:54:17,153 --> 00:54:18,552
May I get in?
- Yeah.

1047
00:54:23,519 --> 00:54:25,043
It needs painting.

1048
00:54:25,088 --> 00:54:26,646
I keep wanting to do it.

1049
00:54:26,689 --> 00:54:27,656
- I'll help you.

1050
00:54:27,690 --> 00:54:29,658
I'd like to do that.

1051
00:54:29,692 --> 00:54:32,718
- Oaroline hates the gondola
more than anything.

1052
00:54:32,762 --> 00:54:34,593
I don't know why.

1053
00:54:46,943 --> 00:54:48,934
- [Sighs]

1054
00:54:52,281 --> 00:54:54,272
[Squeaking]

1055
00:54:56,285 --> 00:55:01,018
- What's she like,
Deirdre?

1056
00:55:01,057 --> 00:55:05,858
- She's very determined.

1057
00:55:05,895 --> 00:55:08,363
Very strong personality.

1058
00:55:08,398 --> 00:55:12,300
She decides what needs
to be done and does it.

1059
00:55:12,335 --> 00:55:13,859
- That's how I'd want to be.

1060
00:55:13,903 --> 00:55:15,632
- Well, so would I.

1061
00:55:15,671 --> 00:55:17,195
I don't suppose
I'll ever manage it.

1062
00:55:17,240 --> 00:55:18,298
[Both laugh]

1063
00:55:18,341 --> 00:55:19,569
- Me neither.

1064
00:55:41,597 --> 00:55:43,258
Oan you help me get out?
- Oh, sure.

1065
00:56:01,551 --> 00:56:04,543
[Bees buzzing]

1066
00:56:10,393 --> 00:56:13,021
- [Speaking foreign language]

1067
00:56:13,062 --> 00:56:14,552
More, more.

1068
00:56:19,502 --> 00:56:21,299
- Portia.

1069
00:56:21,337 --> 00:56:24,704
Pete, I wish
you wouldn't let her do this.

1070
00:56:24,740 --> 00:56:25,798
You're not even protected.

1071
00:56:25,842 --> 00:56:29,005
- You want to help?
- No.

1072
00:56:29,045 --> 00:56:31,673
[Buzzing]

1073
00:56:31,714 --> 00:56:33,545
- Gracias.

1074
00:56:33,583 --> 00:56:35,141
- Oan't I do it?
- No.

1075
00:56:35,184 --> 00:56:37,015
Oertainly not.
You're not to climb up there.

1076
00:56:37,053 --> 00:56:38,213
- I'll do it.
- Not at all.

1077
00:56:38,254 --> 00:56:39,721
- Oan I help?
- Sure.

1078
00:56:39,755 --> 00:56:43,020
Take the net
up the other ladder.

1079
00:56:43,059 --> 00:56:44,924
- I'll take that.

1080
00:56:53,436 --> 00:56:55,734
[Bees buzzing]

1081
00:56:55,771 --> 00:57:00,140
Portia, stay away
from the bees.

1082
00:57:00,176 --> 00:57:02,235
- Pull the net towards you.

1083
00:57:02,278 --> 00:57:06,772
- Let me get higher.
- Okay.

1084
00:57:06,816 --> 00:57:08,374
A little more.
- Okay.

1085
00:57:11,888 --> 00:57:14,220
[Loud buzzing]
Ow!

1086
00:57:14,257 --> 00:57:15,224
- Oareful.

1087
00:57:15,258 --> 00:57:16,816
[Buzzing]

1088
00:57:16,859 --> 00:57:18,724
Omar.

1089
00:57:18,761 --> 00:57:19,728
- Ow!

1090
00:57:19,762 --> 00:57:21,389
- [Gasps]
- [Screaming]

1091
00:57:21,430 --> 00:57:22,624
- Omar!
- Omar!

1092
00:57:22,665 --> 00:57:23,757
Thud!

1093
00:57:27,003 --> 00:57:28,129
- No!

1094
00:57:29,605 --> 00:57:31,197
- Omar?

1095
00:57:31,240 --> 00:57:32,832
Omar.

1096
00:58:35,905 --> 00:58:38,897
[Soft beeping]

1097
00:59:36,899 --> 00:59:38,298
[Sighs]

1098
00:59:38,334 --> 00:59:40,802
Oh, Omar.

1099
00:59:40,836 --> 00:59:43,532
Omar, the doctor's
made a mistake.

1100
00:59:43,572 --> 00:59:46,063
He thinks I'm your girlfriend.

1101
00:59:49,145 --> 00:59:54,048
Oan you hear me?

1102
00:59:54,083 --> 00:59:58,713
Oan you feel me?

1103
00:59:58,754 --> 01:00:00,221
But it's all right.

1104
01:00:00,256 --> 01:00:03,555
I found Deirdre's phone number
in your book.

1105
01:00:03,592 --> 01:00:06,925
I left a message on her machine.

1106
01:00:06,962 --> 01:00:11,661
Maybe she'll come soon,
and then everything...

1107
01:00:11,701 --> 01:00:13,066
can you hear me?

1108
01:00:13,102 --> 01:00:15,832
Do you know what I'm saying?

1109
01:00:15,871 --> 01:00:19,568
Deirdre's coming.

1110
01:00:19,608 --> 01:00:21,940
Oh, please blink.

1111
01:00:25,781 --> 01:00:28,579
[Birds singing]

1112
01:00:28,617 --> 01:00:31,643
[Motor rumbling]

1113
01:00:49,171 --> 01:00:50,160
- No way.

1114
01:01:13,763 --> 01:01:15,287
[Grunts]

1115
01:01:23,839 --> 01:01:24,931
[Engine turns over]

1116
01:01:24,974 --> 01:01:27,135
[Motor rumbling]

1117
01:01:27,176 --> 01:01:30,907
- Let me just show you
your bedroom and bathroom.

1118
01:01:30,946 --> 01:01:34,006
Did you know Omar was allergic
to bee sting?

1119
01:01:34,049 --> 01:01:35,243
- I did not.

1120
01:01:35,284 --> 01:01:39,050
But I'm not surprised.

1121
01:01:39,088 --> 01:01:42,182
[Shouting and whistling]

1122
01:01:42,224 --> 01:01:45,193
[Cattle lowing]

1123
01:01:45,227 --> 01:01:49,596
[Whooping and horses neighing]

1124
01:01:49,632 --> 01:01:51,099
- Are those gauchos?

1125
01:01:51,133 --> 01:01:52,225
- No.

1126
01:01:52,268 --> 01:01:54,532
Oh, yes.
Gauchos.

1127
01:01:54,570 --> 01:01:58,438
Oowboys.

1128
01:01:58,474 --> 01:02:00,442
There's something
I must tell you.

1129
01:02:00,476 --> 01:02:01,909
No, thanks.

1130
01:02:01,944 --> 01:02:04,276
The doctor, Dr. Pereira,

1131
01:02:04,313 --> 01:02:08,807
he's taken very good care
of Omar, but, um...

1132
01:02:08,851 --> 01:02:12,048
he's made a silly mistake.

1133
01:02:12,087 --> 01:02:16,251
He thinks I'm Omar's lover.

1134
01:02:17,593 --> 01:02:18,719
- Oh.

1135
01:02:18,761 --> 01:02:20,592
- It's the sort of thing
he would think.

1136
01:02:20,629 --> 01:02:22,062
He's Latin American.

1137
01:02:22,097 --> 01:02:24,395
They see the world
in a certain way.

1138
01:02:24,433 --> 01:02:27,630
But I didn't correct him.

1139
01:02:27,670 --> 01:02:29,399
- Why not?

1140
01:02:29,438 --> 01:02:34,398
- As I said, Dr. Pereira
is the way men are here.

1141
01:02:34,443 --> 01:02:37,674
They like to think
of men and women involved,

1142
01:02:37,713 --> 01:02:40,045
romantically involved.

1143
01:02:40,082 --> 01:02:42,312
I thought that
if the doctor thinks that,

1144
01:02:42,351 --> 01:02:46,515
that Omar is loved...
that I love him...

1145
01:02:46,555 --> 01:02:50,355
then he would
take very special care of him.

1146
01:02:50,392 --> 01:02:51,416
- Moo!

1147
01:02:51,460 --> 01:02:53,087
- But of course,
now that you're here...

1148
01:02:53,128 --> 01:02:55,528
- No, that's all right.

1149
01:02:55,564 --> 01:02:57,191
Whatever works best for Omar,

1150
01:02:57,233 --> 01:03:00,259
I don't care
what a doctor thinks.

1151
01:03:00,302 --> 01:03:02,429
Let him think I'm Omar's sister.

1152
01:03:02,471 --> 01:03:04,564
- Oh, you don't look
like his sister,

1153
01:03:04,607 --> 01:03:08,270
nothing like.

1154
01:03:08,310 --> 01:03:11,279
[Cattle mooing loudly]

1155
01:03:11,313 --> 01:03:14,282
[Men whooping and hollering]

1156
01:03:14,316 --> 01:03:17,285
[Motor rumbling]

1157
01:03:17,319 --> 01:03:20,311
[Mooing and shouting continues]

1158
01:03:26,929 --> 01:03:28,726
- He's in this ward,

1159
01:03:28,764 --> 01:03:29,731
on the right.

1160
01:03:29,765 --> 01:03:30,891
I'll wait outside.

1161
01:03:30,933 --> 01:03:32,264
- Okay, thank you.

1162
01:04:03,232 --> 01:04:07,794
- Mm.

1163
01:04:07,836 --> 01:04:11,203
My god.

1164
01:04:11,240 --> 01:04:13,868
Why are you here?

1165
01:04:13,909 --> 01:04:16,810
- Arden called me.

1166
01:04:16,845 --> 01:04:18,312
You were in a coma.

1167
01:04:23,752 --> 01:04:25,811
Has Arden been visiting you?

1168
01:04:25,854 --> 01:04:28,049
- Have you met her?

1169
01:04:28,090 --> 01:04:29,819
- Of course,
I'm staying in the house.

1170
01:04:29,858 --> 01:04:32,326
- Don't you like it?

1171
01:04:32,361 --> 01:04:33,851
Isn't it amazing,

1172
01:04:33,896 --> 01:04:37,059
the house and everything?

1173
01:04:37,099 --> 01:04:41,331
- Do you remember what happened?

1174
01:04:41,370 --> 01:04:44,498
With the bees?

1175
01:04:44,540 --> 01:04:46,735
- No.

1176
01:04:46,775 --> 01:04:50,438
I don't remember anything
that happened that day clearly.

1177
01:04:57,319 --> 01:04:59,253
- Are you a friend
of our poor Omar?

1178
01:04:59,288 --> 01:05:01,518
- Yes, I'm very worried
about Omar.

1179
01:05:01,557 --> 01:05:02,751
- You must not worry.

1180
01:05:02,791 --> 01:05:04,452
You are too beautiful to worry.

1181
01:05:04,493 --> 01:05:08,122
All the women who visit Omar
are beautiful.

1182
01:05:08,163 --> 01:05:11,189
His recovery
has nothing to do with me.

1183
01:05:11,233 --> 01:05:14,031
It is the beauty of women
that cured him.

1184
01:05:35,090 --> 01:05:37,718
- Where did you
get these pajamas?

1185
01:05:37,760 --> 01:05:38,954
- I don't know.

1186
01:05:38,994 --> 01:05:42,293
I woke up wearing them.

1187
01:05:42,331 --> 01:05:45,061
- Did Arden bring them?

1188
01:05:45,100 --> 01:05:46,965
They may have belonged to Jules.

1189
01:05:47,002 --> 01:05:49,903
You are wearing
Jules Gund's pajamas.

1190
01:05:49,938 --> 01:05:51,769
[Both chuckle]

1191
01:05:51,807 --> 01:05:53,297
- Mmm.

1192
01:05:53,342 --> 01:05:56,072
- Do you think she's changed
her mind about authorization?

1193
01:05:56,111 --> 01:05:58,579
- Well, I'm not very sure
about Oaroline.

1194
01:05:58,614 --> 01:05:59,945
- We'll see about her.

1195
01:05:59,982 --> 01:06:01,415
What about Arden?

1196
01:06:01,450 --> 01:06:04,283
- She's leaning my way.

1197
01:06:04,319 --> 01:06:07,345
Our way.

1198
01:06:07,389 --> 01:06:09,448
- And the other one,
the brother?

1199
01:06:09,491 --> 01:06:11,789
- Adam?
- Mm-hmm.

1200
01:06:11,827 --> 01:06:13,522
- He's always been on my side.

1201
01:06:13,562 --> 01:06:15,530
And he says
he'll help me with Oaroline,

1202
01:06:15,564 --> 01:06:16,861
and I said I'd help him.

1203
01:06:16,899 --> 01:06:18,196
- Help him with what?

1204
01:06:18,233 --> 01:06:19,860
What can you help him with?

1205
01:06:19,902 --> 01:06:21,529
- It's nothing, really.

1206
01:06:21,570 --> 01:06:23,561
He just wants me
to carry something for him

1207
01:06:23,605 --> 01:06:25,470
when I go back to the States.

1208
01:06:25,507 --> 01:06:26,997
- Oarry what?

1209
01:06:27,042 --> 01:06:30,637
- Just some things.

1210
01:06:30,679 --> 01:06:32,510
- What things?

1211
01:06:32,548 --> 01:06:33,674
- Some...

1212
01:06:33,715 --> 01:06:35,649
pieces of jewelry.

1213
01:06:35,684 --> 01:06:38,016
Stuff like that.
[Clattering]

1214
01:06:38,053 --> 01:06:39,111
- Jewelry?

1215
01:06:39,154 --> 01:06:42,885
Did you say you would?

1216
01:06:42,925 --> 01:06:45,894
Omar, you're crazy.

1217
01:06:45,928 --> 01:06:47,156
It's smuggling.

1218
01:06:47,196 --> 01:06:48,788
He's asking you
to smuggle for him.

1219
01:06:48,831 --> 01:06:50,992
[Titters]
You'll go to jail.

1220
01:06:51,033 --> 01:06:53,126
- He wouldn't ask me
to do anything criminal.

1221
01:06:53,168 --> 01:06:54,260
He's not that type.

1222
01:06:54,303 --> 01:06:56,328
- Anyone who asks you
to take something

1223
01:06:56,371 --> 01:06:58,236
secretly out of the country
for him

1224
01:06:58,273 --> 01:07:00,070
is that type.

1225
01:07:00,109 --> 01:07:02,771
- He's been very helpful to me
with the biography.

1226
01:07:02,811 --> 01:07:04,005
And that's what I'm here for:

1227
01:07:04,046 --> 01:07:06,014
To get authorization
for the biography.

1228
01:07:06,048 --> 01:07:07,743
- This is not the way to get it.

1229
01:07:07,783 --> 01:07:09,808
- I'm doing it my way.
Everything's fine.

1230
01:07:09,852 --> 01:07:11,581
- Everything is not fine, Omar.

1231
01:07:11,620 --> 01:07:13,645
If it were, I wouldn't be here.

1232
01:07:13,689 --> 01:07:14,849
- I didn't ask you to come here.

1233
01:07:14,890 --> 01:07:16,255
- Oh, I'm sorry.

1234
01:07:16,291 --> 01:07:19,192
I flew 5,000 miles
because you were in a coma.

1235
01:07:19,228 --> 01:07:20,252
A coma!

1236
01:07:20,295 --> 01:07:21,455
- Stop.

1237
01:07:21,497 --> 01:07:24,022
I'm sorry, I didn't mean it.

1238
01:07:24,066 --> 01:07:27,365
I just... I wish you wouldn't
treat me like a baby.

1239
01:07:27,402 --> 01:07:29,029
- Then don't act like a baby.

1240
01:07:29,071 --> 01:07:31,039
Don't agree to smuggle jewelry.

1241
01:07:31,073 --> 01:07:32,506
Don't fall out of a tree.

1242
01:07:32,541 --> 01:07:35,032
- Falling out of a tree
was an accident.

1243
01:07:35,077 --> 01:07:36,635
- You know what I think
about accidents.

1244
01:07:36,678 --> 01:07:39,044
- Accidents happen to people,
Deirdre.

1245
01:07:39,081 --> 01:07:42,983
We can't all be perfect
like you.

1246
01:07:43,018 --> 01:07:45,885
- I'm not perfect.

1247
01:07:45,921 --> 01:07:48,822
I know I'm not perfect.

1248
01:07:48,857 --> 01:07:50,119
I don't think I am.

1249
01:07:50,159 --> 01:07:52,389
I'm just trying
to help you, Omar,

1250
01:07:52,427 --> 01:07:56,557
because I love you.

1251
01:07:56,598 --> 01:07:58,532
You really wish I hadn't come?

1252
01:07:58,567 --> 01:08:01,536
- No.

1253
01:08:01,570 --> 01:08:02,901
- Because I can leave.

1254
01:08:02,938 --> 01:08:04,098
I can leave whenever you want.

1255
01:08:04,139 --> 01:08:05,766
- No.
[Sighs]

1256
01:08:05,807 --> 01:08:07,035
Want you to stay.

1257
01:08:15,651 --> 01:08:17,949
- Omar,
you've broken your wrist.

1258
01:08:17,986 --> 01:08:20,318
Let me wipe the soup
off your face.

1259
01:08:36,838 --> 01:08:38,237
- Adam!

1260
01:08:42,411 --> 01:08:45,312
- So how is
our poor young friend?

1261
01:08:45,347 --> 01:08:47,542
I hear he's recovering.

1262
01:08:47,583 --> 01:08:50,143
- His girlfriend has arrived

1263
01:08:50,185 --> 01:08:51,880
to comfort him,

1264
01:08:51,920 --> 01:08:55,083
and hopefully
to take him home.

1265
01:08:55,123 --> 01:08:57,148
Where's Pete?

1266
01:08:57,192 --> 01:08:58,591
- Taking a shower.

1267
01:09:06,368 --> 01:09:08,768
So...

1268
01:09:08,804 --> 01:09:12,934
to what do I owe
this pleasure?

1269
01:09:12,975 --> 01:09:14,533
It really is a pleasure,
you know?

1270
01:09:23,719 --> 01:09:28,122
Well, here we are.

1271
01:09:28,156 --> 01:09:31,523
To the pleasure of you.

1272
01:09:31,560 --> 01:09:36,361
- How sweet you are.

1273
01:09:36,398 --> 01:09:38,025
- Not bad.

1274
01:09:38,066 --> 01:09:39,033
Not bad at all.

1275
01:09:39,067 --> 01:09:40,864
Please, sit down.

1276
01:09:40,902 --> 01:09:42,893
- It's supposed to be
a cocktail.

1277
01:09:46,742 --> 01:09:48,209
- Oocktail.

1278
01:09:48,243 --> 01:09:50,711
What a lovely word.

1279
01:09:50,746 --> 01:09:52,441
If only one could drink it

1280
01:09:52,481 --> 01:09:54,381
where a cocktail
should be drunk,

1281
01:09:54,416 --> 01:09:56,475
sitting on a barstool

1282
01:09:56,518 --> 01:09:59,954
somewhere dark, secluded.

1283
01:09:59,988 --> 01:10:01,114
But liquor is liquor

1284
01:10:01,156 --> 01:10:02,680
wherever you go in the world,
isn't it?

1285
01:10:02,724 --> 01:10:05,557
- It's a Manhattan,

1286
01:10:05,594 --> 01:10:08,495
or half a Manhattan,
since you have no bourbon.

1287
01:10:08,530 --> 01:10:09,895
- A Manhattan.

1288
01:10:09,931 --> 01:10:12,161
That's your Moscow.

1289
01:10:12,200 --> 01:10:13,224
Hmm?

1290
01:10:13,268 --> 01:10:15,236
"Oh, Olga, Olga,
let us go to Moscow.

1291
01:10:15,270 --> 01:10:17,500
There's no place in the world
like Moscow."

1292
01:10:20,942 --> 01:10:22,000
- Adam, I want to ask you,

1293
01:10:22,044 --> 01:10:23,773
do you think
I was wrong to stay here?

1294
01:10:23,812 --> 01:10:26,178
- What do you mean?

1295
01:10:26,214 --> 01:10:28,682
- You know what I mean.

1296
01:10:28,717 --> 01:10:32,244
When Jules came back
with Arden.

1297
01:10:32,287 --> 01:10:33,845
- I didn't judge you.

1298
01:10:33,889 --> 01:10:36,551
It was your affair and Jules'.

1299
01:10:36,591 --> 01:10:38,252
- She was so pathetic.

1300
01:10:38,293 --> 01:10:39,920
It was as if he'd picked up
a stray kitten

1301
01:10:39,961 --> 01:10:42,862
and brought it home,

1302
01:10:42,898 --> 01:10:44,559
a pregnant kitten.

1303
01:10:44,599 --> 01:10:46,760
- Yeah.

1304
01:10:46,802 --> 01:10:49,202
- Now I think she's changed
her mind about the biography,

1305
01:10:49,237 --> 01:10:50,602
as you have.

1306
01:10:50,639 --> 01:10:51,936
- I never opposed it.

1307
01:10:51,973 --> 01:10:52,940
Why should we?

1308
01:10:52,974 --> 01:10:54,942
A biography is nothing,

1309
01:10:54,976 --> 01:10:56,944
an account of the facts
written by,

1310
01:10:56,978 --> 01:11:00,106
well, just for all we know,
some academic hack.

1311
01:11:00,148 --> 01:11:01,809
Though I hope not.

1312
01:11:01,850 --> 01:11:03,875
Maybe he'll surprise us.

1313
01:11:03,919 --> 01:11:05,318
Poor boy.

1314
01:11:05,354 --> 01:11:06,878
What a thing to happen.

1315
01:11:06,922 --> 01:11:08,549
A bee, can you imagine?

1316
01:11:08,590 --> 01:11:10,319
- It's his own fault.

1317
01:11:10,359 --> 01:11:11,383
Why did he come here?

1318
01:11:11,426 --> 01:11:14,054
He has no business here,
hack or not.

1319
01:11:14,096 --> 01:11:17,224
- Supposing Jules
had written something himself.

1320
01:11:17,265 --> 01:11:19,733
Had he?

1321
01:11:19,768 --> 01:11:21,201
Yes, he had.

1322
01:11:21,236 --> 01:11:22,464
I thought so.

1323
01:11:22,504 --> 01:11:25,405
And it would have to be
personal, autobiographical,

1324
01:11:25,440 --> 01:11:27,908
'cause Jules
was not an inventive writer.

1325
01:11:27,943 --> 01:11:30,241
<i>And as The Gondola
was about our parents' lives,</i>

1326
01:11:30,278 --> 01:11:31,905
this other manuscript...

1327
01:11:31,947 --> 01:11:33,744
- Which no longer exists.

1328
01:11:33,782 --> 01:11:35,579
- Which no longer exists...

1329
01:11:35,617 --> 01:11:39,747
would be about his life with you
and Arden in this place.

1330
01:11:39,788 --> 01:11:42,518
And for all I know,

1331
01:11:42,557 --> 01:11:45,924
even about Pete and me.

1332
01:11:45,961 --> 01:11:50,261
- How could any outsider
understand this place

1333
01:11:50,298 --> 01:11:54,132
or what it was like
to all live here together

1334
01:11:54,169 --> 01:11:57,696
or what it's like now
without him?

1335
01:11:57,739 --> 01:11:59,263
- Yes.

1336
01:12:01,576 --> 01:12:03,203
You know,
you could leave tomorrow

1337
01:12:03,245 --> 01:12:04,735
if you wanted to,

1338
01:12:04,780 --> 01:12:06,873
any time you choose.

1339
01:12:06,915 --> 01:12:09,975
- You very well know,
I have no money.

1340
01:12:10,018 --> 01:12:12,213
How could I get
the fare together?

1341
01:12:12,254 --> 01:12:13,812
Don't you think I haven't
thought of it,

1342
01:12:13,855 --> 01:12:16,221
that I don't sit up there
pretending to paint,

1343
01:12:16,258 --> 01:12:19,557
brooding over
where I might be instead?

1344
01:12:19,594 --> 01:12:20,720
I need a real drink.

1345
01:12:20,762 --> 01:12:23,731
How about you?

1346
01:12:23,765 --> 01:12:25,392
Scotch.
- Yeah.

1347
01:12:25,434 --> 01:12:27,902
- Not getting very far
on just vermouth.

1348
01:12:27,936 --> 01:12:32,396
[Distant thunder crashes]

1349
01:12:32,441 --> 01:12:34,170
Adam, do you like life?

1350
01:12:34,209 --> 01:12:35,403
- [Chuckles]

1351
01:12:35,444 --> 01:12:38,072
Well, I wouldn't like
to live forever.

1352
01:12:38,113 --> 01:12:42,174
But um, for a little while,
yes, but...

1353
01:12:42,217 --> 01:12:44,344
yes, I like it.

1354
01:12:44,386 --> 01:12:45,978
- But living here?

1355
01:12:46,021 --> 01:12:47,579
You wouldn't rather
be somewhere else,

1356
01:12:47,622 --> 01:12:48,589
New York, London?

1357
01:12:48,623 --> 01:12:50,921
- No.
- Why not?

1358
01:12:50,959 --> 01:12:52,688
- Because you have
to care about...

1359
01:12:52,727 --> 01:12:55,753
or at least pretend to care
about everything:

1360
01:12:55,797 --> 01:12:58,197
Politics, fashion, culture.

1361
01:12:58,233 --> 01:12:59,598
It's just exhausting.

1362
01:12:59,634 --> 01:13:02,296
- What I wouldn't give
to see some new painters,

1363
01:13:02,337 --> 01:13:06,034
a new play, go to the opera.

1364
01:13:06,074 --> 01:13:08,599
Yes, I know.

1365
01:13:08,643 --> 01:13:11,407
To Moscow, Olga.

1366
01:13:11,446 --> 01:13:15,041
- Yeah.

1367
01:13:15,083 --> 01:13:16,744
This is a very potent drink.

1368
01:13:16,785 --> 01:13:20,084
Perhaps I should not
have indulged in a refill.

1369
01:13:23,859 --> 01:13:26,692
Tell me something.
Was there ever a letter?

1370
01:13:26,728 --> 01:13:27,820
Did Jules really write to you

1371
01:13:27,863 --> 01:13:29,626
saying he didn't want
a biography?

1372
01:13:29,664 --> 01:13:30,790
- No.

1373
01:13:30,832 --> 01:13:32,390
But I know
he wouldn't have wanted it.

1374
01:13:32,434 --> 01:13:33,401
- How would you know that?

1375
01:13:33,435 --> 01:13:34,993
- Because he destroyed
the manuscript.

1376
01:13:35,036 --> 01:13:36,560
[Thunder rumbling]

1377
01:13:36,605 --> 01:13:38,232
- He destroyed it himself?

1378
01:13:38,273 --> 01:13:39,570
- He wanted no one to know

1379
01:13:39,608 --> 01:13:42,406
what only concerned himself
and me.

1380
01:13:42,444 --> 01:13:44,241
So no matter
what you and Arden decide,

1381
01:13:44,279 --> 01:13:47,305
I shall never allow
this biography to be written,

1382
01:13:47,349 --> 01:13:49,613
even if he gets stung
by 100 bees.

1383
01:13:52,988 --> 01:13:55,980
[Rustling]

1384
01:14:01,329 --> 01:14:02,694
- Excuse me.

1385
01:14:02,731 --> 01:14:05,165
Oan you tell me the way
to the mill house, please?

1386
01:14:05,200 --> 01:14:07,634
- You have to go back this way

1387
01:14:07,669 --> 01:14:11,696
and then
through the bamboo grove.

1388
01:14:11,740 --> 01:14:12,968
- Through there.

1389
01:14:13,008 --> 01:14:14,066
- Thank you.

1390
01:14:18,914 --> 01:14:20,609
- What do you think of her?

1391
01:14:20,649 --> 01:14:22,549
- What do you?

1392
01:14:22,584 --> 01:14:25,644
- I don't see her with Omar,

1393
01:14:25,687 --> 01:14:27,120
her personality.

1394
01:14:27,155 --> 01:14:30,249
But I don't know either of them
very well.

1395
01:14:30,292 --> 01:14:32,453
What do you think?

1396
01:14:42,137 --> 01:14:44,571
Will you miss them
when they're gone?

1397
01:14:44,606 --> 01:14:46,631
- No.

1398
01:14:46,675 --> 01:14:48,734
- I mean Omar.

1399
01:14:48,777 --> 01:14:49,971
Will you miss Omar?

1400
01:14:54,616 --> 01:14:58,074
Do you love him?

1401
01:14:58,119 --> 01:15:01,577
- No.

1402
01:15:01,623 --> 01:15:07,391
No, I don't love Omar.

1403
01:15:07,429 --> 01:15:10,125
What?
Why did you ask me that?

1404
01:15:10,165 --> 01:15:13,293
Omar didn't say anything to you
about me

1405
01:15:13,335 --> 01:15:15,360
when you went to see him
in the hospital?

1406
01:15:15,403 --> 01:15:17,166
- No,
I just thought,

1407
01:15:17,205 --> 01:15:19,036
if I were you...

1408
01:15:19,074 --> 01:15:22,805
- If you were me, what?

1409
01:15:22,844 --> 01:15:24,869
- I might love him.

1410
01:15:24,913 --> 01:15:26,210
- [Laughs]

1411
01:15:26,247 --> 01:15:28,647
Well, it's as you said, Pete.

1412
01:15:28,683 --> 01:15:29,980
We hardly know him.

1413
01:15:30,018 --> 01:15:32,646
He's only been here
for a short time,

1414
01:15:32,687 --> 01:15:34,211
he has a girlfriend,

1415
01:15:34,255 --> 01:15:36,052
and he's leaving soon.

1416
01:15:36,091 --> 01:15:38,992
The doctor says he can travel
in a few days.

1417
01:15:39,027 --> 01:15:41,222
They're both leaving.

1418
01:15:41,262 --> 01:15:42,229
I'm glad.

1419
01:15:42,263 --> 01:15:46,029
[Rustling]

1420
01:15:46,067 --> 01:15:49,059
[Birds chirping]

1421
01:15:50,605 --> 01:15:53,597
[Insects clicking and buzzing]

1422
01:16:02,484 --> 01:16:04,509
- Mr. Gund?

1423
01:16:04,552 --> 01:16:06,713
- Who calls?

1424
01:16:06,755 --> 01:16:07,949
- Hello.

1425
01:16:07,989 --> 01:16:09,422
- Hello.

1426
01:16:09,457 --> 01:16:11,789
- I could come back another time
if you're not free.

1427
01:16:11,826 --> 01:16:13,191
- Not free?

1428
01:16:13,228 --> 01:16:14,923
As you can see, I'm quite free,

1429
01:16:14,963 --> 01:16:16,624
hopelessly free,

1430
01:16:16,665 --> 01:16:19,031
for the rest of my life.

1431
01:16:19,067 --> 01:16:22,434
This is Jesus,
and you must be, uh... Deborah.

1432
01:16:22,470 --> 01:16:23,562
- Deirdre.

1433
01:16:23,605 --> 01:16:25,095
- [Inhales]
Deirdre.

1434
01:16:25,140 --> 01:16:27,472
May I offer you something?

1435
01:16:27,509 --> 01:16:29,739
- Oh, just some mineral water
if you have it.

1436
01:16:29,778 --> 01:16:31,712
- Mineral water, hmm.

1437
01:16:31,746 --> 01:16:33,213
How about a dry martini?

1438
01:16:33,248 --> 01:16:34,306
- [Chuckles]

1439
01:16:34,349 --> 01:16:35,373
No.
[Clears throat]

1440
01:16:35,417 --> 01:16:36,384
No, thank you.

1441
01:16:36,418 --> 01:16:37,385
- So you must be,

1442
01:16:37,419 --> 01:16:39,614
um... Omar's paramour.

1443
01:16:39,654 --> 01:16:41,246
It's so difficult
finding the right word

1444
01:16:41,289 --> 01:16:42,483
to describe a relationship.

1445
01:16:42,524 --> 01:16:43,491
[Chuckles]

1446
01:16:43,525 --> 01:16:44,685
At least my relationships.

1447
01:16:44,726 --> 01:16:47,490
They're all too complicated
for mere words.

1448
01:16:47,529 --> 01:16:49,326
- Paramour
is not the right word.

1449
01:16:49,364 --> 01:16:53,232
I wouldn't use it to describe
Omar's and my relationship.

1450
01:16:53,268 --> 01:16:55,930
- Do sit down, my dear.
You look as if you might bolt.

1451
01:16:55,970 --> 01:16:58,905
I've offended you, no doubt.

1452
01:16:58,940 --> 01:17:01,272
Good.

1453
01:17:01,309 --> 01:17:02,401
You know, in my youth,

1454
01:17:02,444 --> 01:17:04,674
I used to call my partners
my paramours.

1455
01:17:04,713 --> 01:17:07,443
It's such a lovely word
to describe a lovely situation.

1456
01:17:07,482 --> 01:17:11,179
And as a result, I remained
a youth for a very long time.

1457
01:17:11,219 --> 01:17:13,687
The aging process was retarded,
but alas,

1458
01:17:13,722 --> 01:17:16,350
one morning I woke up and...

1459
01:17:16,391 --> 01:17:19,019
I was an old man
who talks too much.

1460
01:17:19,060 --> 01:17:20,857
But it is you who've come
to talk to me, yes,

1461
01:17:20,895 --> 01:17:24,956
I have no doubt,
about the authorization.

1462
01:17:24,999 --> 01:17:28,196
As you've probably heard,
I'm on Omar's side.

1463
01:17:28,236 --> 01:17:30,500
We have made our arrangement.

1464
01:17:30,538 --> 01:17:32,301
- That is what I've come
to talk to you about,

1465
01:17:32,340 --> 01:17:34,331
what you call an arrangement.

1466
01:17:34,375 --> 01:17:35,467
- So he has told you about it?

1467
01:17:35,510 --> 01:17:36,477
- He has,

1468
01:17:36,511 --> 01:17:40,208
and I consider it blackmail.

1469
01:17:40,248 --> 01:17:42,808
You said you had made a bargain
with Omar.

1470
01:17:42,851 --> 01:17:45,046
You asked him to smuggle
certain items out of the country

1471
01:17:45,086 --> 01:17:47,213
in return for your help
in getting him authorization.

1472
01:17:47,255 --> 01:17:48,620
I...

1473
01:17:48,656 --> 01:17:49,987
call that blackmail.

1474
01:17:50,024 --> 01:17:51,821
- "Smuggle," "blackmail."

1475
01:17:51,860 --> 01:17:55,057
My, my, you do have
a romantic imagination.

1476
01:17:55,096 --> 01:17:56,723
- I will not allow him to do it.

1477
01:17:56,765 --> 01:17:58,596
And besides,
he's the wrong person for it.

1478
01:17:58,633 --> 01:17:59,691
- I agree with you.

1479
01:17:59,734 --> 01:18:01,292
Omar is certainly not
the right person.

1480
01:18:01,336 --> 01:18:04,271
Unlike you, he is not practical.

1481
01:18:04,305 --> 01:18:10,175
But you will be returning
to the United States as well?

1482
01:18:10,211 --> 01:18:12,406
- Are you trying to make
a little bargain with me now?

1483
01:18:12,447 --> 01:18:13,505
- Please, do sit down.

1484
01:18:13,548 --> 01:18:15,015
I'm enjoying your company.
Sit down.

1485
01:18:15,049 --> 01:18:16,516
You're so invigorating.
[Chuckles]

1486
01:18:16,551 --> 01:18:18,485
It's a pity
you have no sense of adventure.

1487
01:18:18,520 --> 01:18:20,351
- I certainly have a sense
of what's legal

1488
01:18:20,388 --> 01:18:21,855
and what is not.

1489
01:18:21,890 --> 01:18:24,620
- You know,

1490
01:18:24,659 --> 01:18:26,354
one day, you will regret this.

1491
01:18:26,394 --> 01:18:29,693
You will regret having come
all the way to south America

1492
01:18:29,731 --> 01:18:33,861
and not involving yourself
in what you encounter here.

1493
01:18:33,902 --> 01:18:35,767
You will think, "Oh, why?

1494
01:18:35,804 --> 01:18:39,205
Oh, why
did I not smuggle those things?"

1495
01:18:39,240 --> 01:18:41,231
- So it is smuggling.

1496
01:18:44,412 --> 01:18:45,879
- Well, you read too many books.

1497
01:18:45,914 --> 01:18:47,939
Or perhaps you don't even
read books anymore.

1498
01:18:47,982 --> 01:18:51,042
You probably just read
criticism of books.

1499
01:18:51,085 --> 01:18:52,552
- Mr. Gund,

1500
01:18:52,587 --> 01:18:55,055
you must consider your little
bargain with Omar dissolved.

1501
01:18:55,089 --> 01:18:56,215
Neither he nor I

1502
01:18:56,257 --> 01:18:58,088
will be able to help you
in this business.

1503
01:18:58,126 --> 01:18:59,388
We'll have to get Oaroline

1504
01:18:59,427 --> 01:19:01,327
somehow to agree
to authorization without you.

1505
01:19:01,362 --> 01:19:04,126
- Mm-hmm.
How will you do that?

1506
01:19:04,165 --> 01:19:05,826
- We can try,

1507
01:19:05,867 --> 01:19:07,664
honestly try,

1508
01:19:07,702 --> 01:19:10,535
without resorting to bargains
and blackmail.

1509
01:19:10,572 --> 01:19:12,836
- Hmm.

1510
01:19:12,874 --> 01:19:16,503
It seems a bit stupid to me,
if I may be so blunt,

1511
01:19:16,544 --> 01:19:19,172
to alienate me like this.

1512
01:19:19,214 --> 01:19:21,808
After all, what is stopping me
changing my mind?

1513
01:19:21,850 --> 01:19:23,147
- Oh.

1514
01:19:23,184 --> 01:19:25,118
Excuse me, I...

1515
01:19:25,153 --> 01:19:27,417
I understood
you wanted a biography.

1516
01:19:27,455 --> 01:19:33,018
I didn't think your support
was variable or could be bought.

1517
01:19:33,061 --> 01:19:36,428
<i>Grac¨ªas, Jesus.</i>

1518
01:19:36,464 --> 01:19:39,865
<i>Grac¨ªas.</i>

1519
01:19:39,901 --> 01:19:43,393
Well, I admire your gumption.

1520
01:19:44,572 --> 01:19:45,834
But I think it best

1521
01:19:45,874 --> 01:19:49,708
that this situation be resolved
between Omar and myself.

1522
01:19:49,744 --> 01:19:51,473
The arrangement was made
with Omar,

1523
01:19:51,512 --> 01:19:54,208
so it is up to Omar
to dissolve it.

1524
01:19:54,249 --> 01:19:56,444
I have enjoyed our little chat.

1525
01:19:59,287 --> 01:20:01,152
Please excuse me.

1526
01:20:11,399 --> 01:20:14,368
[Wistful piano and violin music]

1527
01:20:14,402 --> 01:20:22,400
* *

1528
01:20:27,682 --> 01:20:30,674
[sheep bleating]

1529
01:20:36,291 --> 01:20:37,588
- Mrs. Gund.

1530
01:20:37,625 --> 01:20:40,594
[Soft music continues]

1531
01:20:40,628 --> 01:20:43,358
* *

1532
01:20:43,398 --> 01:20:46,925
These are lovely.

1533
01:20:46,968 --> 01:20:49,766
- Are you fond of art?

1534
01:20:49,804 --> 01:20:50,828
- It's not my field,

1535
01:20:50,872 --> 01:20:55,309
but some paintings
I like very much.

1536
01:20:55,343 --> 01:20:56,469
I have been hoping to talk...

1537
01:20:56,511 --> 01:21:01,210
- What kind of paintings
do you like very much?

1538
01:21:01,249 --> 01:21:03,217
- The impressionists,

1539
01:21:03,251 --> 01:21:07,017
Oezanne and Monet, van Gogh.

1540
01:21:07,055 --> 01:21:08,750
Perhaps they weren't
all impressionists,

1541
01:21:08,790 --> 01:21:13,159
or were they?

1542
01:21:13,194 --> 01:21:15,890
- As far you need be concerned,
they were.

1543
01:21:15,930 --> 01:21:18,398
* *

1544
01:21:18,433 --> 01:21:19,866
- May I speak to you?

1545
01:21:19,901 --> 01:21:21,391
- Of course you may.

1546
01:21:21,436 --> 01:21:23,904
Sit.

1547
01:21:23,938 --> 01:21:25,428
Sit.

1548
01:21:28,409 --> 01:21:29,376
- May I?

1549
01:21:29,410 --> 01:21:33,346
- Of course.

1550
01:21:33,381 --> 01:21:34,575
Little to the left, please.

1551
01:21:34,615 --> 01:21:37,584
[Piano music continues]

1552
01:21:37,618 --> 01:21:45,616
* *

1553
01:21:46,728 --> 01:21:47,854
- I'd like to assure you

1554
01:21:47,895 --> 01:21:50,022
that Omar intends
to work very closely

1555
01:21:50,064 --> 01:21:52,692
with you all on the biography.

1556
01:21:52,734 --> 01:21:54,429
If you knew what this is

1557
01:21:54,469 --> 01:21:55,766
for Omar,

1558
01:21:55,803 --> 01:21:57,703
how very much depends on it
for him

1559
01:21:57,739 --> 01:21:59,866
to get authorization
and write this book.

1560
01:21:59,907 --> 01:22:03,866
- I am not concerned
with Omar's needs.

1561
01:22:03,911 --> 01:22:05,276
I have other...

1562
01:22:10,752 --> 01:22:12,379
different allegiances.

1563
01:22:12,420 --> 01:22:13,682
- To Jules Gund?

1564
01:22:13,721 --> 01:22:15,712
- I don't think this is really
any of your business.

1565
01:22:15,757 --> 01:22:17,054
But yes, to my husband.

1566
01:22:17,091 --> 01:22:21,050
* *

1567
01:22:21,095 --> 01:22:25,725
And to myself, for that matter.

1568
01:22:25,767 --> 01:22:28,167
- Why are you
withholding authorization?

1569
01:22:28,202 --> 01:22:31,000
Perhaps if you told me,
I could address your concerns.

1570
01:22:31,039 --> 01:22:32,063
- Shh.

1571
01:22:32,106 --> 01:22:35,075
[Gentle piano music continues]

1572
01:22:35,109 --> 01:22:37,907
* *

1573
01:22:37,945 --> 01:22:40,743
Do you recognize it?

1574
01:22:40,782 --> 01:22:42,750
- It sounds familiar.

1575
01:22:42,784 --> 01:22:46,515
- It's Poulenc,

1576
01:22:46,554 --> 01:22:51,457
<i>Tres Lent et Calme.</i>

1577
01:22:51,492 --> 01:22:56,759
- I hope
you will consider reconsidering.

1578
01:22:56,798 --> 01:23:00,598
- I have already discussed this
with Omar.

1579
01:23:00,635 --> 01:23:02,728
I have told him more than once

1580
01:23:02,770 --> 01:23:04,670
that I will not
change my decision.

1581
01:23:04,705 --> 01:23:07,173
- But Arden has changed hers.

1582
01:23:07,208 --> 01:23:10,541
- Miss Langdon has her reasons;
I have mine.

1583
01:23:10,578 --> 01:23:13,547
[Soothing piano music]

1584
01:23:13,581 --> 01:23:15,549
* *

1585
01:23:15,583 --> 01:23:17,210
Isn't it marvelous?

1586
01:23:17,251 --> 01:23:21,551
* *

1587
01:23:21,589 --> 01:23:24,057
- I think I'm wasting your time.

1588
01:23:24,092 --> 01:23:27,220
- Time is not a very precious
commodity around here.

1589
01:23:27,261 --> 01:23:29,729
- But you've made up your mind.

1590
01:23:29,764 --> 01:23:32,232
- I made it up long ago,

1591
01:23:32,266 --> 01:23:34,461
long before Omar arrived.

1592
01:23:34,502 --> 01:23:38,199
- Then there's really no point
in me or Omar talking to you.

1593
01:23:38,239 --> 01:23:39,672
- Not about that subject,

1594
01:23:39,707 --> 01:23:43,905
but we could talk
about something else.

1595
01:23:43,945 --> 01:23:45,913
Art?

1596
01:23:45,947 --> 01:23:49,178
But that's not your field.

1597
01:23:49,217 --> 01:23:51,583
Music?

1598
01:23:51,619 --> 01:23:54,144
Or is music
not your field either?

1599
01:23:56,457 --> 01:23:58,925
But surely you like this.

1600
01:23:58,960 --> 01:24:00,154
How could you not?

1601
01:24:00,194 --> 01:24:05,393
* *

1602
01:24:05,433 --> 01:24:07,230
- No, thank you.

1603
01:24:09,737 --> 01:24:11,329
- [Inhales sharply]

1604
01:24:11,372 --> 01:24:12,930
* *

1605
01:24:12,974 --> 01:24:16,034
[humming]

1606
01:24:16,077 --> 01:24:18,102
* *

1607
01:24:22,483 --> 01:24:24,781
[rustling and clinking]

1608
01:24:31,759 --> 01:24:34,660
- But why do you need Omar?

1609
01:24:34,695 --> 01:24:36,560
- I didn't want you to know.

1610
01:24:36,597 --> 01:24:38,656
It was to be a secret.

1611
01:24:38,699 --> 01:24:39,893
It was for you, you idiot.

1612
01:24:39,934 --> 01:24:41,731
I wanted you to have the money.

1613
01:24:41,769 --> 01:24:42,895
- Why?

1614
01:24:42,937 --> 01:24:44,404
For what?
- [Sighs]

1615
01:24:44,438 --> 01:24:46,303
- I have a good business
of my own.

1616
01:24:46,340 --> 01:24:48,672
I don't need more money.
You do.

1617
01:24:48,709 --> 01:24:49,801
I'm happy.

1618
01:24:49,844 --> 01:24:51,277
- What, here with me?

1619
01:24:51,312 --> 01:24:53,712
I don't think you know much
about happiness, my friend.

1620
01:24:53,748 --> 01:24:55,010
- Do you?

1621
01:24:55,049 --> 01:24:57,574
- Oh, I gave up on all that
stuff a long time ago.

1622
01:24:57,618 --> 01:24:59,586
- You pretend you have.

1623
01:24:59,620 --> 01:25:02,180
Don't I make you happy,
at least sometimes?

1624
01:25:02,223 --> 01:25:03,850
- Yes, of course.

1625
01:25:03,891 --> 01:25:08,123
- So why are you trying
to send me away?

1626
01:25:08,162 --> 01:25:10,528
- Because I don't want you
wasting yourself on me.

1627
01:25:10,565 --> 01:25:13,193
I'm an old man,

1628
01:25:13,234 --> 01:25:16,260
"a paltry thing,
a tattered coat upon a stick."

1629
01:25:16,304 --> 01:25:18,204
Make a life for yourself,

1630
01:25:18,239 --> 01:25:20,867
for god's sake.

1631
01:25:20,908 --> 01:25:22,808
- Look at me.

1632
01:25:22,843 --> 01:25:24,310
Go on, look.

1633
01:25:24,345 --> 01:25:25,778
- I'm looking.

1634
01:25:25,813 --> 01:25:29,647
I'm 40 years old.

1635
01:25:29,684 --> 01:25:32,585
I've lived with you
for 25 years.

1636
01:25:34,755 --> 01:25:38,885
I don't want any other life.

1637
01:25:38,926 --> 01:25:41,827
- 25 years.

1638
01:25:41,862 --> 01:25:43,830
Hmm.

1639
01:25:43,864 --> 01:25:45,957
You're a sweet boy.

1640
01:25:46,000 --> 01:25:48,264
And I've always loved you,
and I love you now.

1641
01:26:00,615 --> 01:26:04,210
- But there is someone
who needs money to leave.

1642
01:26:06,220 --> 01:26:08,017
- Oh, Oaroline, yes.

1643
01:26:12,226 --> 01:26:14,558
- Don't involve Omar in this.

1644
01:26:14,595 --> 01:26:15,892
- Hmm?

1645
01:26:15,930 --> 01:26:18,592
- I can get much better price
than he ever could.

1646
01:26:18,633 --> 01:26:21,602
If not in Montevideo,
then in Buenos Aires.

1647
01:26:21,636 --> 01:26:22,694
- You can?

1648
01:26:22,737 --> 01:26:23,704
How?

1649
01:26:23,738 --> 01:26:25,569
- I have contacts.

1650
01:26:25,606 --> 01:26:29,406
- So how much do you think
you will make with these?

1651
01:26:29,443 --> 01:26:32,378
- Enough for
where she wants to be.

1652
01:26:32,413 --> 01:26:34,847
- Really?

1653
01:26:34,882 --> 01:26:38,648
Supposing we exact
a small exchange with Oaroline.

1654
01:26:38,686 --> 01:26:41,985
Supposing the money
you make for her,

1655
01:26:42,023 --> 01:26:44,389
she takes the cash and leaves.

1656
01:26:44,425 --> 01:26:46,086
- Quite a bit of cash.

1657
01:26:46,127 --> 01:26:47,151
- Yes.

1658
01:26:47,194 --> 01:26:49,059
And in return
for that bit of cash,

1659
01:26:49,096 --> 01:26:50,825
we could make a bargain
with her.

1660
01:26:50,865 --> 01:26:52,833
I suggest
she might want to make over

1661
01:26:52,867 --> 01:26:57,736
her part of Ocho Rios
to you.

1662
01:26:57,772 --> 01:27:00,332
You'd be 1/3 partner
with Portia and myself,

1663
01:27:00,374 --> 01:27:01,500
and of course, as you know,

1664
01:27:01,542 --> 01:27:03,669
we're more accommodating
than Oaroline

1665
01:27:03,711 --> 01:27:06,839
and more used to signing things.

1666
01:27:06,881 --> 01:27:08,508
So perhaps you could,
if you want to,

1667
01:27:08,549 --> 01:27:12,110
start one of
your moneymaking schemes.

1668
01:27:12,153 --> 01:27:15,850
Thousands of acres of soybeans

1669
01:27:15,890 --> 01:27:19,053
blowing in the wind.

1670
01:27:19,093 --> 01:27:20,390
- My god.

1671
01:27:20,428 --> 01:27:23,886
How I'd make this place
work for us.

1672
01:27:23,931 --> 01:27:26,058
Oh.

1673
01:27:40,848 --> 01:27:42,907
- I'm going to Las Golondrinas
for a few days.

1674
01:27:42,950 --> 01:27:45,043
I just wanted you to know.
- Why?

1675
01:27:45,086 --> 01:27:46,747
- I don't feel comfortable here.

1676
01:27:46,787 --> 01:27:48,220
I want all these people
to go away.

1677
01:27:48,255 --> 01:27:50,780
But as they only incapacitate
themselves and multiply,

1678
01:27:50,825 --> 01:27:52,315
I'm going away myself.

1679
01:27:52,360 --> 01:27:53,987
Oall me when the coast is clear.

1680
01:27:54,028 --> 01:27:55,825
- I'll do no such thing.

1681
01:27:55,863 --> 01:27:57,694
Go if you want,
but don't give me orders.

1682
01:27:57,732 --> 01:27:59,165
- Goodness.

1683
01:27:59,200 --> 01:28:01,532
Sounds as if you're the one
who needs to get away from here.

1684
01:28:11,178 --> 01:28:12,202
- Oaroline.

1685
01:28:12,246 --> 01:28:13,975
- I wonder
if Luis can get me there.

1686
01:28:14,014 --> 01:28:17,347
<i>Esta b¨ªen, Lu¨ªs?
- A su d¨ªspos¨ªc¨ªon, senora.</i>

1687
01:28:17,385 --> 01:28:20,252
- Are you leaving
without talking to him,

1688
01:28:20,287 --> 01:28:21,413
to Omar?

1689
01:28:21,455 --> 01:28:22,422
Omar.

1690
01:28:22,456 --> 01:28:23,445
- Why should I talk to him?

1691
01:28:23,491 --> 01:28:24,583
I've talked a lot to him

1692
01:28:24,625 --> 01:28:28,618
and to his
rather unpleasant girlfriend.

1693
01:28:28,662 --> 01:28:31,187
- You're afraid that if you
stay, you'll change your mind.

1694
01:28:31,232 --> 01:28:33,632
- I'm afraid if I stay,
I'll lose my mind.

1695
01:28:40,708 --> 01:28:42,471
- "My dear Oaroline,

1696
01:28:42,510 --> 01:28:44,637
"I have a confession to make.

1697
01:28:44,678 --> 01:28:47,875
"I am a jewel thief.

1698
01:28:47,915 --> 01:28:51,646
"I have secretly kept
all my mother's diamonds.

1699
01:28:51,685 --> 01:28:54,882
"Graciously,
I beg you to absolve me

1700
01:28:54,922 --> 01:28:58,722
"by accepting them
from my guilty hands.

1701
01:28:58,759 --> 01:29:01,819
Don't overdo it."

1702
01:29:01,862 --> 01:29:02,829
- "Forgive me, if you can,

1703
01:29:02,863 --> 01:29:04,421
"and live happily
on the proceeds

1704
01:29:04,465 --> 01:29:06,990
"wherever you may choose.

1705
01:29:07,034 --> 01:29:09,366
"Pete and I have each other

1706
01:29:09,403 --> 01:29:12,429
"and need almost nothing more.

1707
01:29:12,473 --> 01:29:16,341
"But there is one fairly small
favor you can do for us.

1708
01:29:16,377 --> 01:29:18,937
"In return
for Mother's diamonds,

1709
01:29:18,979 --> 01:29:23,006
"would you relinquish
your 1/3 share of Ocho Rios?

1710
01:29:23,050 --> 01:29:25,041
"Pete has great plans
for the estate

1711
01:29:25,085 --> 01:29:28,020
"that I cannot even pretend
to understand.

1712
01:29:28,055 --> 01:29:30,489
"A new chapter
will soon begin for you

1713
01:29:30,524 --> 01:29:31,718
"and if, perchance,

1714
01:29:31,759 --> 01:29:33,693
"something is weighing
on your conscience...

1715
01:29:33,727 --> 01:29:35,854
"and who among us
is without blame?

1716
01:29:35,896 --> 01:29:37,796
<i>"Humanum errare est...</i>

1717
01:29:37,832 --> 01:29:40,824
"rid yourself of it
with one small gesture.

1718
01:29:40,868 --> 01:29:44,304
"Allow the boy
to write the biography

1719
01:29:44,338 --> 01:29:48,035
"yours is still
the one voice he needs.

1720
01:29:48,075 --> 01:29:49,406
Adam."

1721
01:30:07,862 --> 01:30:09,727
- Where is everyone?

1722
01:30:09,763 --> 01:30:12,231
- They're busy
doing whatever they do,

1723
01:30:12,266 --> 01:30:14,234
forging paintings,

1724
01:30:14,268 --> 01:30:16,236
raising killer bees, I guess,

1725
01:30:16,270 --> 01:30:17,931
and smuggling jewels.

1726
01:30:22,109 --> 01:30:23,633
- Well,
can you please go find them

1727
01:30:23,677 --> 01:30:25,440
and tell them we're back
from the hospital?

1728
01:30:31,285 --> 01:30:32,252
- Find whom?

1729
01:30:32,286 --> 01:30:35,915
- Arden... and everyone.

1730
01:30:35,956 --> 01:30:37,355
Oaroline.

1731
01:30:37,391 --> 01:30:38,983
- Oaroline.

1732
01:30:39,026 --> 01:30:41,290
You certainly
need to speak to Oaroline.

1733
01:30:47,234 --> 01:30:48,462
[Knocks]

1734
01:30:57,311 --> 01:30:58,801
- What are you drawing?

1735
01:31:13,928 --> 01:31:16,396
- Are you finished?

1736
01:31:16,430 --> 01:31:17,488
I'm sorry, Portia,

1737
01:31:17,531 --> 01:31:19,590
but I need to talk to Omar.

1738
01:31:24,538 --> 01:31:26,438
[Whispers]
Run along.

1739
01:31:27,942 --> 01:31:29,239
Oan you believe it?

1740
01:31:29,276 --> 01:31:30,868
Oaroline has left.

1741
01:31:30,911 --> 01:31:34,506
And without a word to us
about the authorization.

1742
01:31:34,548 --> 01:31:36,413
I'll have to go after her
and speak to her.

1743
01:31:36,450 --> 01:31:40,011
I think she's enjoying this.

1744
01:31:40,054 --> 01:31:42,284
[Whispers]
These people are awful.

1745
01:31:42,323 --> 01:31:47,693
- If anyone speaks to Oaroline,
it'll have to be me.

1746
01:31:47,728 --> 01:31:51,596
- I think I might be better
at handling a person like that.

1747
01:31:51,632 --> 01:31:53,395
- I don't want to handle anyone.

1748
01:31:53,434 --> 01:31:56,926
I hate that attitude.

1749
01:31:56,971 --> 01:31:59,439
- Omar,

1750
01:31:59,473 --> 01:32:01,065
what's the matter with you?

1751
01:32:06,747 --> 01:32:09,648
I'm sorry.

1752
01:32:09,683 --> 01:32:12,015
I'm sorry, you've been ill.

1753
01:32:12,052 --> 01:32:15,852
You've only just
come out of the hospital.

1754
01:32:15,889 --> 01:32:17,948
You're not yourself.

1755
01:32:17,992 --> 01:32:19,721
And really,
you're not in a fit state

1756
01:32:19,760 --> 01:32:21,523
to go running
after crazy Oaroline.

1757
01:32:21,562 --> 01:32:23,723
- Please, Deirdre,

1758
01:32:23,764 --> 01:32:25,197
leave it to me.

1759
01:32:25,232 --> 01:32:26,324
- Darling...

1760
01:32:26,367 --> 01:32:27,595
- Would you just let me rest?

1761
01:32:39,980 --> 01:32:42,710
[Indistinct shouting
and splashing]

1762
01:33:15,315 --> 01:33:16,976
- Omar, "Las Golondrinas"

1763
01:33:17,017 --> 01:33:20,544
means little birds
that fly and sing.

1764
01:33:20,587 --> 01:33:25,047
That is what we do here,
as you can see.

1765
01:33:25,092 --> 01:33:28,152
Jules was always welcome here.

1766
01:33:28,195 --> 01:33:30,891
He lived with his two women
at Ocho Rios,

1767
01:33:30,931 --> 01:33:35,391
and sometimes
he had to come up for air...

1768
01:33:35,436 --> 01:33:38,234
when Oaroline
was too much for him.

1769
01:33:38,272 --> 01:33:39,967
- And Arden was too little.

1770
01:33:43,944 --> 01:33:45,309
- Don't you want to swim?

1771
01:33:45,345 --> 01:33:46,972
We have plenty of suits.

1772
01:33:47,014 --> 01:33:48,311
Yes?

1773
01:33:48,348 --> 01:33:50,908
You don't have to put that arm
in the water, no?

1774
01:33:50,951 --> 01:33:52,646
<i>El brac¨ªto en el agua,
para que?</i>

1775
01:33:52,686 --> 01:33:53,744
<i>No.</i>

1776
01:33:53,787 --> 01:33:57,279
<i>Traele...traele, W¨ªlson...</i>

1777
01:33:57,324 --> 01:33:58,655
- No, no, no.
- Oomo no, no, no, no?

1778
01:33:58,692 --> 01:34:01,320
<i>S¨ª.
Plunk! Plunk! Plunk!</i>

1779
01:34:01,361 --> 01:34:03,556
[Shouting and splashing]

1780
01:34:05,799 --> 01:34:09,963
Jules was very, very attractive.

1781
01:34:10,003 --> 01:34:11,868
And depressive, of course.

1782
01:34:11,905 --> 01:34:14,533
But that made him
even more attractive,

1783
01:34:14,575 --> 01:34:17,703
like Hamlet
or someone out of Dostoyevsky.

1784
01:34:17,745 --> 01:34:19,212
[Chuckles]

1785
01:34:19,246 --> 01:34:22,875
He had the knack
of making each woman he met

1786
01:34:22,916 --> 01:34:27,148
feel she was the only one
who truly understood him.

1787
01:34:27,187 --> 01:34:28,449
Only women.

1788
01:34:28,489 --> 01:34:29,888
He didn't care for men,

1789
01:34:29,923 --> 01:34:32,289
nor they for him.

1790
01:34:32,326 --> 01:34:35,227
And he was writing this book,

1791
01:34:35,262 --> 01:34:38,425
another book
to make him even more famous.

1792
01:34:38,465 --> 01:34:39,830
We thought it was thrilling.

1793
01:34:39,867 --> 01:34:42,097
Perhaps we were all in it.

1794
01:34:42,136 --> 01:34:45,902
And each one of us
thought she was his muse.

1795
01:34:45,939 --> 01:34:48,772
And would go down in history,
no?

1796
01:34:55,048 --> 01:34:58,916
- God knows
what she's telling him.

1797
01:34:58,952 --> 01:35:00,442
Every woman who ever met Jules

1798
01:35:00,487 --> 01:35:04,184
is convinced she understood him
better than I did,

1799
01:35:04,224 --> 01:35:06,556
or Arden, for that matter.

1800
01:35:06,593 --> 01:35:09,960
- You know what I think?

1801
01:35:09,997 --> 01:35:13,296
That he wasn't writing a book
at all.

1802
01:35:13,333 --> 01:35:15,301
He was talking about it

1803
01:35:15,335 --> 01:35:17,633
to impress us,

1804
01:35:17,671 --> 01:35:20,640
but he found he couldn't.

1805
01:35:20,674 --> 01:35:25,043
And that made him...

1806
01:35:25,078 --> 01:35:26,545
he couldn't bear the thought

1807
01:35:26,580 --> 01:35:29,981
of not being
a celebrated author anymore.

1808
01:35:30,017 --> 01:35:34,215
Admired and famous and...

1809
01:35:34,254 --> 01:35:37,246
and everyone
hopelessly in love with him.

1810
01:35:40,127 --> 01:35:41,890
Ah, Wilson.

1811
01:35:41,929 --> 01:35:43,055
- Senora.

1812
01:35:43,096 --> 01:35:44,085
<i>- Grac¨ªas.</i>

1813
01:35:48,602 --> 01:35:50,934
<i>Perm¨ªso.</i>

1814
01:35:50,971 --> 01:35:52,563
[Crowd chattering indistinctly]

1815
01:35:52,606 --> 01:35:54,130
- Tango.

1816
01:35:54,174 --> 01:35:55,664
<i>Tango.
Puedes.</i>

1817
01:35:55,709 --> 01:35:57,643
<i>- Puedo.
- Puedes.</i>

1818
