<i>- Puedes.
- Puedo, puedo.</i>

1819
01:36:08,288 --> 01:36:09,915
- Maybe we'll meet
in the States.

1820
01:36:09,957 --> 01:36:11,356
I'd like that very much,

1821
01:36:11,391 --> 01:36:15,259
although maybe you prefer
to forget all about me.

1822
01:36:15,295 --> 01:36:17,525
- I want to give you
a farewell present.

1823
01:36:17,564 --> 01:36:20,192
About the biography,
go ahead and write it.

1824
01:36:20,234 --> 01:36:23,533
Explain us to ourselves,
if you can.

1825
01:36:23,570 --> 01:36:25,037
I'll be interested

1826
01:36:25,072 --> 01:36:28,564
to read your interpretation
or invention.

1827
01:36:30,911 --> 01:36:34,870
I grant you my authorization.

1828
01:36:34,915 --> 01:36:36,314
Isn't that what you wanted?

1829
01:36:36,350 --> 01:36:38,750
What you came here for?

1830
01:36:38,785 --> 01:36:40,810
- Of course.

1831
01:36:40,854 --> 01:36:42,754
And I'm very grateful to you.

1832
01:36:45,926 --> 01:36:49,054
- Deirdre anyway,
will be pleased.

1833
01:36:49,096 --> 01:36:51,894
- But what about Jules' letter
that he didn't want a biography?

1834
01:36:51,932 --> 01:36:53,331
- Jules never wrote
such a letter.

1835
01:36:53,367 --> 01:36:55,562
I made that up.

1836
01:36:55,602 --> 01:36:58,901
But he did try
and write a second book.

1837
01:36:58,939 --> 01:37:01,203
There is a manuscript.
It does exist.

1838
01:37:01,241 --> 01:37:05,041
No one's ever read it except me.

1839
01:37:05,078 --> 01:37:06,102
Jules never finished it.

1840
01:37:06,146 --> 01:37:08,580
He couldn't.

1841
01:37:08,615 --> 01:37:11,516
Shall I tell you
about the last scene?

1842
01:37:11,551 --> 01:37:14,850
The last he wrote
and then he couldn't go on?

1843
01:37:14,888 --> 01:37:18,346
In this last scene, Arden and I
are in the gondola,

1844
01:37:18,392 --> 01:37:21,293
and we loathe each other
as we never did.

1845
01:37:21,328 --> 01:37:23,819
Though, perhaps
that's what he was waiting for.

1846
01:37:23,864 --> 01:37:25,354
But in the gondola,

1847
01:37:25,399 --> 01:37:27,526
we have a terrible fight,

1848
01:37:27,567 --> 01:37:28,966
a physical fight.

1849
01:37:29,002 --> 01:37:31,630
And I push Arden overboard.

1850
01:37:31,672 --> 01:37:32,866
But you know what?

1851
01:37:32,906 --> 01:37:34,897
The water isn't deep enough.

1852
01:37:34,942 --> 01:37:38,639
So I keep on pushing her down
and down.

1853
01:37:38,679 --> 01:37:41,204
- Did you intend to publish it?

1854
01:37:41,248 --> 01:37:43,148
- There were times
when I felt that I had to,

1855
01:37:43,183 --> 01:37:45,549
that it was a responsibility,
a duty,

1856
01:37:45,585 --> 01:37:48,816
to literature, if that
doesn't sound too grandiose.

1857
01:37:48,855 --> 01:37:52,552
- I don't believe
any of us has such a duty.

1858
01:37:52,592 --> 01:37:55,390
I believe literature
takes its life from us,

1859
01:37:55,429 --> 01:37:57,056
not the other way around.

1860
01:37:57,097 --> 01:38:00,089
- Is this the belief
of a professor of literature?

1861
01:38:00,133 --> 01:38:04,832
- Oh, I'm afraid
this is the other Omar,

1862
01:38:04,871 --> 01:38:07,601
the misguided caliph
who burned all the books.

1863
01:38:07,641 --> 01:38:10,166
You know,
the entire library of Alexandria

1864
01:38:10,210 --> 01:38:12,235
was fed into
the bathhouse boilers,

1865
01:38:12,279 --> 01:38:15,214
700,000 papyrus scrolls.

1866
01:38:15,248 --> 01:38:17,842
It took six months
to burn them all up.

1867
01:38:17,884 --> 01:38:21,342
[Distant chatter and music]

1868
01:38:21,388 --> 01:38:24,357
[Festive guitar music]

1869
01:38:24,391 --> 01:38:32,389
* *

1870
01:38:38,905 --> 01:38:40,202
- Let me take that.

1871
01:38:40,240 --> 01:38:42,572
[Thudding
and indistinct chatter]

1872
01:38:46,179 --> 01:38:47,578
<i>Grac¨ªas.</i>

1873
01:38:54,921 --> 01:38:56,252
[Knocks]

1874
01:39:04,631 --> 01:39:07,065
- I was just coming down
to say good-bye.

1875
01:39:07,100 --> 01:39:08,533
- I've come up.

1876
01:39:17,944 --> 01:39:20,640
- You must be very happy
with your success.

1877
01:39:20,680 --> 01:39:21,908
- My success?

1878
01:39:21,948 --> 01:39:24,348
- You've achieved everything
you came for.

1879
01:39:24,384 --> 01:39:27,353
With all three of us,
that's 100% success.

1880
01:39:27,387 --> 01:39:28,684
- Arden,

1881
01:39:28,722 --> 01:39:30,417
I'll come back soon.

1882
01:39:30,457 --> 01:39:32,584
- I know.
You have to interview all of us.

1883
01:39:32,626 --> 01:39:34,389
- That's not
what I'm coming back for.

1884
01:39:42,235 --> 01:39:43,668
- Omar?

1885
01:39:48,341 --> 01:39:49,569
- I'll be right down.

1886
01:39:55,082 --> 01:39:58,381
Deirdre's always afraid
of missing her plane.

1887
01:39:58,418 --> 01:39:59,612
She never has.

1888
01:39:59,653 --> 01:40:00,620
- Have you?

1889
01:40:00,654 --> 01:40:02,315
- Maybe twice, three times.

1890
01:40:02,355 --> 01:40:03,583
Whatever.

1891
01:40:03,623 --> 01:40:05,648
There are worse things in life
than missing a plane.

1892
01:40:05,692 --> 01:40:10,561
- Well,
try not to miss this one.

1893
01:40:10,597 --> 01:40:12,326
- You're right.

1894
01:40:12,365 --> 01:40:13,559
[Chuckles]

1895
01:40:13,600 --> 01:40:16,068
You know what I think?

1896
01:40:16,103 --> 01:40:18,298
Those bees
knew what they were doing.

1897
01:40:18,338 --> 01:40:23,401
They stung me so I'd remember
what I was here for.

1898
01:40:23,443 --> 01:40:25,434
Not for my own selfish reasons,

1899
01:40:25,479 --> 01:40:27,913
not just to have a good time
and be happy...

1900
01:40:27,948 --> 01:40:29,813
- But to get your PhD.

1901
01:40:29,850 --> 01:40:32,011
- And write the book.

1902
01:40:32,052 --> 01:40:33,781
- And when it's published,

1903
01:40:33,820 --> 01:40:35,981
I hope you'll send us
one copy each.

1904
01:40:36,022 --> 01:40:38,422
And please inscribe it,

1905
01:40:38,458 --> 01:40:42,588
"With best wishes,
from professor Razaghi, PhD."

1906
01:40:42,629 --> 01:40:44,859
- Professor Razaghi.

1907
01:40:44,898 --> 01:40:47,628
It sounds like a stage magician.

1908
01:40:47,667 --> 01:40:50,864
The kind that makes pigeons
fly out of a top hat.

1909
01:40:50,904 --> 01:40:52,269
[Both chuckle]

1910
01:40:52,305 --> 01:40:54,296
- And saws girls in half.

1911
01:41:15,095 --> 01:41:16,426
[Knock at door]

1912
01:41:22,202 --> 01:41:23,260
[Whispers]
Go on.

1913
01:41:29,342 --> 01:41:33,403
- Here you are.

1914
01:41:33,446 --> 01:41:35,778
We're going to miss the plane.

1915
01:41:35,815 --> 01:41:37,248
- Good-bye, Deirdre.

1916
01:41:37,284 --> 01:41:40,811
I hope you and Omar have a safe
and pleasant journey.

1917
01:41:40,854 --> 01:41:44,187
- Thank you for everything.

1918
01:41:44,224 --> 01:41:45,452
Good-bye.

1919
01:41:51,131 --> 01:41:52,291
- Bye.

1920
01:41:59,839 --> 01:42:02,831
[Fire crackling]

1921
01:42:06,913 --> 01:42:09,905
[Water splashing]

1922
01:42:17,424 --> 01:42:20,257
[Fire snapping and crackling]

1923
01:42:49,055 --> 01:42:52,047
[Bell tolling]

1924
01:43:14,848 --> 01:43:15,974
- Hey, Omar.

1925
01:43:16,016 --> 01:43:17,608
- Where you going, Omar?
- I'm in a hurry.

1926
01:43:17,651 --> 01:43:19,380
- Oh, come on.
- Hey! Hey! Hey!

1927
01:43:19,419 --> 01:43:21,478
[Shouting and giggling]

1928
01:43:21,521 --> 01:43:23,148
Knock it off!

1929
01:43:23,189 --> 01:43:25,384
- Hey!

1930
01:43:25,425 --> 01:43:28,519
[Shouting and squealing
continues]

1931
01:43:33,933 --> 01:43:35,628
- In 500 words for Monday,

1932
01:43:35,669 --> 01:43:38,866
I want you to analyze the role
of fate in hardy's novel.

1933
01:43:38,905 --> 01:43:42,739
In Shakespeare,
character is always fate.

1934
01:43:42,776 --> 01:43:44,573
Which we know by now
from experience

1935
01:43:44,611 --> 01:43:45,908
to be absolutely true.

1936
01:43:45,945 --> 01:43:48,072
What happens to me happens

1937
01:43:48,114 --> 01:43:52,073
because I am I.

1938
01:43:52,118 --> 01:43:54,177
Hardy's characters
are caught in situations

1939
01:43:54,220 --> 01:43:57,849
that are impossible
to get out of.

1940
01:43:57,891 --> 01:44:01,952
But are they impossible?

1941
01:44:01,995 --> 01:44:04,691
Suppose a character decides
that he can do something

1942
01:44:04,731 --> 01:44:06,961
about his fate.

1943
01:44:07,000 --> 01:44:08,024
What then?

1944
01:44:08,068 --> 01:44:09,535
[Bell tolling]

1945
01:44:09,569 --> 01:44:11,696
Any hands?

1946
01:44:11,738 --> 01:44:12,705
Oome on, guys.

1947
01:44:12,739 --> 01:44:15,731
[Bell tolling]

1948
01:44:17,677 --> 01:44:20,771
[Students murmuring]

1949
01:44:29,155 --> 01:44:32,124
[Plaintive woodwind music]

1950
01:44:32,158 --> 01:44:37,619
* *

1951
01:44:37,664 --> 01:44:40,997
[rain pattering]

1952
01:44:41,034 --> 01:44:43,434
[Thunder crashes]

1953
01:44:48,375 --> 01:44:49,774
- It's Omar.

1954
01:45:13,299 --> 01:45:15,631
Omar, I found your shoe.

1955
01:45:15,668 --> 01:45:16,965
- My shoe?

1956
01:45:17,003 --> 01:45:19,631
- The one you lost
when the bee stung you.

1957
01:45:19,672 --> 01:45:21,139
Do you still have the other one?

1958
01:45:21,174 --> 01:45:22,368
Then you can wear them.

1959
01:45:22,409 --> 01:45:23,876
- [Panting]

1960
01:45:23,910 --> 01:45:26,310
Thank you, Portia.

1961
01:45:26,346 --> 01:45:28,177
As a matter of fact,
I did keep it

1962
01:45:28,214 --> 01:45:30,478
as a souvenir from my bee sting.

1963
01:45:30,517 --> 01:45:34,214
- I'll go and get it.

1964
01:45:34,254 --> 01:45:36,051
- You can't do this.

1965
01:45:36,089 --> 01:45:37,488
It's wrong.

1966
01:45:37,524 --> 01:45:40,823
Walk in, walk out
whenever it suits you.

1967
01:45:40,860 --> 01:45:42,157
No, you can't.

1968
01:45:42,195 --> 01:45:43,355
- I should have written.

1969
01:45:43,396 --> 01:45:44,795
- Yes, you should have written.

1970
01:45:44,831 --> 01:45:46,264
- I tried to.

1971
01:45:46,299 --> 01:45:48,563
You don't know
how often I tried,

1972
01:45:48,601 --> 01:45:50,068
how many letters I didn't send.

1973
01:45:50,103 --> 01:45:53,368
- A postcard even,
instead of silence, nothing,

1974
01:45:53,406 --> 01:45:54,498
not a word,

1975
01:45:54,541 --> 01:45:56,065
as if we no longer existed.

1976
01:45:56,109 --> 01:45:57,235
- You don't understand.

1977
01:45:57,277 --> 01:45:58,505
- What don't I understand?

1978
01:45:58,545 --> 01:46:01,105
- I was always thinking,
"Go there.

1979
01:46:01,147 --> 01:46:02,580
Go there.
Go there."

1980
01:46:02,615 --> 01:46:04,242
I knew I had to do something.

1981
01:46:04,284 --> 01:46:06,115
I wish
I could have done it right.

1982
01:46:06,152 --> 01:46:08,017
If there was one thing
I could give you,

1983
01:46:08,054 --> 01:46:10,921
it would be for once
to do something right.

1984
01:46:10,957 --> 01:46:13,517
- Well, you can't just
appear like this,

1985
01:46:13,560 --> 01:46:15,027
horribly upsetting everyone

1986
01:46:15,061 --> 01:46:17,996
by turning up
in these fantastic ways.

1987
01:46:18,031 --> 01:46:19,862
- So I should just sit
and do nothing

1988
01:46:19,899 --> 01:46:21,924
and suffer
and miss you?

1989
01:46:21,968 --> 01:46:22,957
- Oh, please, go.

1990
01:46:23,002 --> 01:46:24,833
Just go, Omar.

1991
01:46:35,014 --> 01:46:36,038
- [Sobs]

1992
01:46:36,082 --> 01:46:38,243
- I wanted to give him
his shoe.

1993
01:46:59,272 --> 01:47:00,239
- Omar.

1994
01:47:00,273 --> 01:47:02,207
- Hi, Pete.
- Oome in.

1995
01:47:02,242 --> 01:47:07,179
- Thank you.

1996
01:47:07,213 --> 01:47:11,274
- I'll get you some dry socks.

1997
01:47:11,317 --> 01:47:12,682
- Hail to thee, dear boy.

1998
01:47:12,719 --> 01:47:13,811
Where have you sprung from?

1999
01:47:13,853 --> 01:47:16,344
Oome and sit down.

2000
01:47:16,389 --> 01:47:18,414
Make yourself warm.

2001
01:47:18,458 --> 01:47:20,449
Sit here.
Would you like a drink?

2002
01:47:20,493 --> 01:47:21,892
- Please.
- Good.

2003
01:47:34,574 --> 01:47:36,041
Here you are.
- Thank you.

2004
01:47:36,075 --> 01:47:37,542
- You seem to have developed
the habit

2005
01:47:37,577 --> 01:47:39,408
of popping up at the most
extraordinary times.

2006
01:47:39,445 --> 01:47:41,879
- I'm clumsy and a fool.

2007
01:47:41,915 --> 01:47:43,815
- I used to call myself that.

2008
01:47:43,850 --> 01:47:45,875
But now Pete has set us up
as a corporation,

2009
01:47:45,919 --> 01:47:48,217
I'm not a fool anymore.

2010
01:47:48,254 --> 01:47:50,119
I'm a business.

2011
01:47:50,156 --> 01:47:51,214
And how's your business?

2012
01:47:51,257 --> 01:47:53,851
- I've given it up,
the biography.

2013
01:47:53,893 --> 01:47:54,882
I'm not writing it.

2014
01:47:54,928 --> 01:47:56,418
- Oh.

2015
01:47:56,462 --> 01:47:57,895
Well, quite frankly,
it seemed to me

2016
01:47:57,931 --> 01:47:58,898
that it was, um...

2017
01:47:58,932 --> 01:48:00,229
What was her name?
Deirdre.

2018
01:48:00,266 --> 01:48:02,257
It seemed to me
that it was Deirdre's project

2019
01:48:02,302 --> 01:48:04,770
more than it was yours.

2020
01:48:04,804 --> 01:48:06,897
- Before I even came here,

2021
01:48:06,940 --> 01:48:08,965
I lost a dog.

2022
01:48:09,008 --> 01:48:12,444
And searching for it,
I nearly drowned in a swamp.

2023
01:48:12,478 --> 01:48:14,343
And then it happened again.

2024
01:48:14,380 --> 01:48:15,779
I lost a dog.

2025
01:48:15,815 --> 01:48:19,342
The same dog, Victor.

2026
01:48:19,385 --> 01:48:22,115
And looking for him,
I came to the same swamp,

2027
01:48:22,155 --> 01:48:25,522
and I thought, "Oh, no.
No, not again."

2028
01:48:25,558 --> 01:48:27,458
But I was sinking,

2029
01:48:27,493 --> 01:48:30,519
not in that swamp
but in the biography,

2030
01:48:30,563 --> 01:48:32,861
my whole life.

2031
01:48:32,899 --> 01:48:34,366
- Well, I haven't
the foggiest notion

2032
01:48:34,400 --> 01:48:35,958
of what you're talking about,
dear boy,

2033
01:48:36,002 --> 01:48:37,902
but obviously, you've come
all the way back here

2034
01:48:37,937 --> 01:48:39,199
to save yourself from sinking.

2035
01:48:39,238 --> 01:48:40,227
Welcome.

2036
01:48:40,273 --> 01:48:42,036
- Arden told me to leave.

2037
01:48:42,075 --> 01:48:43,542
She said
I had no right to come here.

2038
01:48:43,576 --> 01:48:45,476
- Oh, we're always saying
things we don't mean,

2039
01:48:45,511 --> 01:48:47,035
especially in this family.

2040
01:48:47,080 --> 01:48:49,708
In fact, we often say
the opposite of what we do mean.

2041
01:48:49,749 --> 01:48:52,217
- Adam sends me away every day.

2042
01:48:52,251 --> 01:48:53,980
He says it's better that way.

2043
01:48:54,020 --> 01:48:55,749
- Yes, "It's better that way,"
which means,

2044
01:48:55,788 --> 01:48:57,551
I can't bear it, but I will.

2045
01:48:57,590 --> 01:48:59,057
It's the Jewish mother in me,
you see.

2046
01:48:59,092 --> 01:49:00,354
- What should I do?

2047
01:49:00,393 --> 01:49:01,519
- Go and see her again.

2048
01:49:01,561 --> 01:49:03,392
- But what if she tells me
to leave again?

2049
01:49:03,429 --> 01:49:05,920
- Then come back here
and tomorrow try again,

2050
01:49:05,965 --> 01:49:09,264
and the day after that
and the day after that.

2051
01:49:09,302 --> 01:49:10,826
[Door slams]

2052
01:49:10,870 --> 01:49:12,531
- Omar!

2053
01:49:31,157 --> 01:49:32,215
- Oome on.

2054
01:49:43,736 --> 01:49:47,263
[People murmuring]

2055
01:49:47,306 --> 01:49:49,274
- This ought to be good.

2056
01:49:49,308 --> 01:49:51,708
- Don't forget he was only
10 or 12 when he wrote it.

2057
01:49:51,744 --> 01:49:52,711
Be kind.

2058
01:49:52,745 --> 01:49:56,306
- [Speaking French]

2059
01:49:56,349 --> 01:49:57,316
[Gasps]

2060
01:49:57,350 --> 01:49:58,317
Hang on.

2061
01:49:58,351 --> 01:49:59,409
I think I know her.

2062
01:50:03,589 --> 01:50:04,886
Excuse me.

2063
01:50:04,924 --> 01:50:07,290
Aren't you Oaroline Gund?

2064
01:50:07,326 --> 01:50:08,793
I'm Deirdre.
We met in...

2065
01:50:08,828 --> 01:50:10,557
- Ocho Rios, of course.

2066
01:50:10,596 --> 01:50:11,824
How could I forget?

2067
01:50:11,864 --> 01:50:14,389
- Hello.

2068
01:50:14,434 --> 01:50:16,402
Nice to meet you.
This is Tim.

2069
01:50:16,436 --> 01:50:17,403
- Hello, nice to meet.

2070
01:50:17,437 --> 01:50:18,904
- Do you live here in Madrid?

2071
01:50:18,938 --> 01:50:20,929
- No, no, we're just visiting.

2072
01:50:20,973 --> 01:50:22,167
We live in New York.

2073
01:50:22,208 --> 01:50:23,334
- Really?
So do I.

2074
01:50:23,376 --> 01:50:26,072
I teach at Oolumbia.

2075
01:50:26,112 --> 01:50:27,340
Do you ever hear from them?

2076
01:50:27,380 --> 01:50:28,847
- I do occasionally.

2077
01:50:28,881 --> 01:50:29,870
They all seem very happy.

2078
01:50:29,916 --> 01:50:31,508
They've turned the land
into vineyards.

2079
01:50:31,551 --> 01:50:32,575
And there's a baby.

2080
01:50:32,618 --> 01:50:33,983
- A baby?

2081
01:50:34,020 --> 01:50:35,317
A boy or a girl?

2082
01:50:35,354 --> 01:50:36,946
- A girl.

2083
01:50:36,989 --> 01:50:39,924
A little sister for Portia.

2084
01:50:39,959 --> 01:50:41,449
And they still keep bees.

2085
01:50:41,494 --> 01:50:43,155
- Oh.
Those bees?

2086
01:50:43,196 --> 01:50:44,163
- It's a business now.

2087
01:50:44,197 --> 01:50:45,926
They sell the honey.

2088
01:50:45,965 --> 01:50:48,331
- How funny to meet you
like this after all these years,

2089
01:50:48,367 --> 01:50:52,599
and we both
live in New York now.

2090
01:50:52,638 --> 01:50:53,627
- Well.

2091
01:50:53,673 --> 01:50:57,370
- Good-bye.

2092
01:50:57,410 --> 01:50:58,377
- Who's that?

2093
01:50:58,411 --> 01:51:00,038
- That's a crazy story.

2094
01:51:00,079 --> 01:51:03,879
- She's not very...
- Give me a second.

2095
01:51:03,916 --> 01:51:05,645
Oaroline.

2096
01:51:05,685 --> 01:51:07,118
Oall me.

2097
01:51:07,153 --> 01:51:08,120
I'm in the phone book.

2098
01:51:08,154 --> 01:51:09,644
The only Deirdre Rothemund,

2099
01:51:09,689 --> 01:51:11,020
West 84th.

2100
01:51:24,504 --> 01:51:27,496
[Applause]

2101
01:51:35,047 --> 01:51:36,742
- So who was that?

2102
01:51:36,783 --> 01:51:38,614
- Someone I met once

2103
01:51:38,651 --> 01:51:40,585
in Uruguay, of all places,

2104
01:51:40,620 --> 01:51:44,317
three years ago.

2105
01:51:44,357 --> 01:51:47,087
[Lively orchestral music begins]

